{"title_page": "Shelby County v. Holder", "text_new": "{{short description|2013 landmark United States Supreme Court case}}\n{{Infobox SCOTUS case\n |Litigants=Shelby County v. Holder\n |ArgueDate=February 27\n |ArgueYear=2013\n |DecideDate=June 25\n |DecideYear=2013\n |FullName=[[Shelby County, Alabama]], Petitioner v. [[Eric Holder|Eric H. Holder, Jr.]], [[United States Attorney General|Attorney General]], et al.\n |USVol=570\n |USPage=529\n |Docket=12-96\n |OralArgument=https://www.oyez.org/cases/2010-2019/2012/2012_12_96/argument\n |ParallelCitations=133 S. Ct. 2612; 186 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 651\n |Prior=Petition denied, 811 [[F. Supp. 2d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infdco20110922a91 424] ([[United States District Court for the District of Columbia|D.D.C.]] 2011); decision affirmed, 679 [[F.3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20120518150 848] ([[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit|D.C. Cir.]] 2012); [[Certiorari|cert]]. granted, {{ussc|568|1006|2012|el=no}}.\n |Subsequent=Remanded, 541 [[F. App'x]] 1 (D.C. Cir. 2013); motion for attorneys' fees denied, 43 [[F. Supp. 3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infdco20140529d46 47] (D.D.C. 2014), affirmed sub. nom., ''Shelby County v. Lynch'', 799 [[F.3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20150901202 1173] (D.C. Cir. 2015); cert. denied, 136 S. Ct. 981 (2016).\n |Holding=Section 4(b) of the [[Voting Rights Act of 1965]] is unconstitutional.\n |Majority=Roberts\n |JoinMajority=Scalia, Kennedy, Thomas, Alito\n |Concurrence=Thomas\n |Dissent=Ginsburg\n |JoinDissent=Breyer, Sotomayor, Kagan\n |LawsApplied=[[Fifteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. amend. XV]]; [[Voting Rights Act of 1965]]\n}}\n\n'''''Shelby County v. Holder''''', 570 U.S. 529 (2013), is a [[list of landmark court decisions in the United States|landmark]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Kealing|first=Jonathan|title=U.S. Supreme Court strikes down key provision of Voting Rights Act|url=http://www.pri.org/stories/politics-society/keywords/stories/politics-society/government/u-s-supreme-court-strikes-down-key-provision-of-voting-rights-act-14209.html|publisher=Public Radio International|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref> [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] case regarding the constitutionality of two provisions of the [[Voting Rights Act of 1965]]: Section 5, which requires certain states and local governments to obtain federal preclearance before implementing any changes to their voting laws or practices; and Section 4(b), which contains the coverage formula that determines which jurisdictions are subjected to preclearance based on their histories of discrimination in voting.<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\">{{ussc|name=Shelby County v. Holder|volume=570|page=529|pin=|year=2013}}.</ref><ref name=\"oyez\">{{cite web|title=SHELBY COUNTY v. HOLDER|publisher=The Oyez Project at IIT Chicago-Kent College of Law|url=https://www.oyez.org/cases/2010-2019/2012/2012_12_96|accessdate=7 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 25, 2013, the Court ruled by a 5-to-4 vote that Section 4(b) is unconstitutional because the coverage formula is based on data over 40 years old, making it no longer responsive to current needs and therefore an impermissible burden on the constitutional principles of [[federalism]] and equal sovereignty of the states.<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\" /><ref name=\"oyez\" /> The Court did not strike down Section 5, but without Section 4(b), no jurisdiction will be subject to Section 5 preclearance unless Congress enacts a new coverage formula.<ref name=\"plain-english\">{{cite web |url= http://www.scotusblog.com/2013/06/details-on-shelby-county-v-holder-in-plain-english |title= Amy Howe, Details on Shelby County v. Holder: In Plain English (Case 12-399) |publisher= SCOTUSblog |date=2013-06-25 |accessdate=June 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nSome critics have said that the ruling has made it easier for state officials to make it harder for Black and other racio-ethnic minority voters to vote.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.pewtrusts.org/research-and-analysis/blogs/stateline/2018/09/04/polling-places-remain-a-target-ahead-of-november-elections|title=Polling Place Politics|website=www.pewtrusts.org|accessdate=2018-09-05}}</ref> Research shows that preclearance led to increases in minority congressional representation and increases in minority turnout.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Ang|first=Desmond|date=2019|title=Do 40-Year-Old Facts Still Matter? Long-Run Effects of Federal Oversight under the Voting Rights Act|url=https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/app.20170572|journal=American Economic Journal: Applied Economics|language=en|volume=11|issue=3|pages=1\u201353|doi=10.1257/app.20170572|issn=1945-7782|via=|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\":10\" /> Five years after the ruling, nearly 1,000 polling places had been closed in the U.S., with many of the closed polling places in predominantly African-American counties. Research shows that the changing of voter locations and reduction in voting locations can reduce voter turnout.<ref name=\":4\" /> There were also cuts to early voting, purges of voter rolls and imposition of strict voter ID laws.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/09/12/politics/voting-rights-federal-commission-election/index.html|title=Discriminatory voter laws have surged in last 5 years, federal commission finds|date=2018|website=CNN}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usccr.gov/pubs/2018/Minority_Voting_Access_2018.pdf|title=Assessment of Minority Voting Rights Access|date=2018|website=U.S. Commission on Civil Rights}}</ref> Virtually all restrictions on voting subsequent to the ruling were by Republicans.<ref name=\":7\"/>\n\n== Background ==\n[[United States Congress|Congress]] enacted the [[Voting Rights Act of 1965]] to address entrenched racial discrimination in voting, \"an insidious and pervasive evil which had been perpetuated in certain parts of our country through unremitting and ingenious defiance of the Constitution\".<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\" /> Section 5 of the Act contains a \"preclearance\" requirement that requires certain states and local governments to obtain a determination by the [[United States Attorney General]] or a three-judge panel of the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia]] that changes to their voting laws or practices do not \"deny or abridge the right to vote on account of race, color, or membership in a language minority group\", before those changes may be enforced.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Section 5 of the Voting Rights Act|url=http://www.justice.gov/crt/about/vot/sec_5/about.php|work=DOJ Civil Rights Division|publisher=United States Department of Justice|accessdate=7 July 2013}}</ref> Section 4(b) contains the coverage formula that determines which states and local governments are subject to preclearance under Section 5. The formula covers jurisdictions that, as of November 1964, November 1968, or November 1972, maintained a prohibited \"test or device\" as a condition of registering to vote or voting and had a voting-age population of which less than 50 percent either were registered to vote or actually voted in that year's presidential election.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title=Section 4 of the Voting Rights Act|url=http://www.justice.gov/crt/about/vot/misc/sec_4.php|work=DOJ Civil Rights Division|publisher=United States Department of Justice|accessdate=7 July 2013|ref=name=Section4DOJ}}</ref> Section 4(a) allows covered jurisdictions that have made sufficient progress in ending discriminatory voting practices to \"bail out\" of the preclearance requirement.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] upheld the preclearance requirement and coverage formula as constitutional [[Congressional power of enforcement|enforcement legislation]] under Section 2 of the [[Fifteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifteenth Amendment]] in ''[[South Carolina v. Katzenbach]]'' (1966).<ref>[https://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/historics/USSC_CR_0383_0301_ZO.html ''South Carolina v. Katzenbach''], 383 U.S. 301 (1966).</ref> The preclearance requirement initially was set to expire five years after enactment, but amendments to the Act in 1970, 1975, and 1982 reauthorized Section 5; the 1970 and 1975 amendments also updated the coverage formula.<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\" /><ref name=\"Democracy\">{{cite book|last=Issacharoff|first=Samuel|title=The Law of Democracy: Legal Structure of the Political Process|year=2012|publisher=Foundation Press|isbn=978-1599419350|edition=4th|author2=Karlan, Pamela S. |author3=Pildes, Richard H.}}</ref>{{rp|571}} The Supreme Court upheld these reauthorizations as constitutional in ''Georgia v. United States'' (1973),<ref>{{ussc|name=Georgia v. United States|link=|volume=411|page=526|pin=|year=1973}}.</ref> ''City of Rome v. United States'' (1980),<ref>{{ussc|name=Rome v. United States|link=|volume=446|page=156|pin=|year=1980}}.</ref> and ''Lopez v. Monterey County'' (1999).<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\" />{{rp|5}}<ref>{{ussc|name=Lopez v. Monterey County|link=|volume=525|page=266|pin=|year=1999}}.</ref> In 2006, Congress reauthorized Section 5 for an additional 25 years, but it did not change the coverage formula from the 1975 version.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nShortly after the 2006 reauthorization, a [[Texas]] utility district sought to bail out from Section 5 preclearance and, in the alternative, challenged the constitutionality of Section 5. The Supreme Court ruled unanimously in ''[[Northwest Austin Municipal Utility District No. 1 v. Holder]]'' that government entities that did not register voters, such as the utility district, had the right to file suit to bail out of coverage. Because this decision resolved the issue, the Court invoked [[constitutional avoidance]] and declined to address the constitutionality of Section 5. Justice Thomas dissented from this portion of the opinion and would have declared Section 5 unconstitutional.<ref>[https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/08pdf/08-322.pdf ''Northwest Austin Municipal Utility District No. 1 v. Holder''], 557 U.S. 193 (2009).</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n=== District Court ===\n[[Shelby County, Alabama|Shelby County]], in the covered jurisdiction of [[Alabama]], sued the [[United States Attorney General|U.S. Attorney General]] in the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia|U.S. District Court for D.C.]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], seeking a [[declaratory judgment]] that sections 4(b) and 5 are [[Facial challenge|facially unconstitutional]] and a permanent [[injunction]] against their enforcement. On September 21, 2011, Judge [[John D. Bates]] upheld the provisions, finding that the evidence before Congress in 2006 was sufficient to justify reauthorizing Section 5 and continuing Section 4(b)'s coverage formula.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Shelby County v. Holder |vol=811 |reporter=F. Supp. 2d |opinion=424 |pinpoint= |court=[[D.D.C.]] |date=2011 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infdco20110922a91 |accessdate=2018-09-02 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nArguing before Judge Bates included [http://blog.al.com/sweethome/2011/02/shelby_county_voting_rights_ca_2.html Kristen Clarke], who argued that it was reasonable for Congress to \"stay the course\" in renewing Section 5 of the Voting Rights Act in order to root out discrimination. Bert Rein, a lawyer for Shelby County, [http://blog.al.com/sweethome/2011/02/shelby_county_voting_rights_ca_2.html argued] that the environment in the country was \"totally different\" when Section 5 was first enacted.\n\n=== Court of Appeals ===\nOn May 18, 2012, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit|U.S. Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit]] affirmed the decision of the District Court upholding the constitutionality of Section 4(b) and Section 5. After surveying the evidence in the Congressional record associated with the 2006 reauthorization of Section 5, the appellate court accepted Congress's conclusion that Section 2 litigation remained inadequate in the covered jurisdictions to protect the rights of minority voters, that Section 5 was therefore still justified, and that the coverage formula continued to pass constitutional muster.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Shelby County v. Holder |vol=679 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=848 |pinpoint= |court=[[D.C. Cir.]] |date=2012 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20120518150 |accessdate=2018-09-02 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n=== Supreme Court ===\nThe Supreme Court granted ''[[writ of certiorari|certiorari]]'' to hear the case on the limited question of \"whether Congress' decision in 2006 to reauthorize Section 5 of the Voting Rights Act under the pre-existing coverage formula of Section 4(b) of the Voting Rights Act exceeded its authority under the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth]] and [[Fifteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifteenth Amendments]] and thus violated the [[Tenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Tenth Amendment]] and [[Article IV of the United States Constitution]].\"<ref>[https://www.supremecourt.gov/orders/courtorders/110912zr_d18e.pdf Certiorari granted, November 9, 2012]</ref> The Supreme Court heard oral arguments on February 27, 2013.<ref>[https://www.supremecourt.gov/oral_arguments/argument_transcripts/12-96.pdf Transcript of Oral Argument from Feb 27, 2013]</ref> Media coverage of the Justices' comments during oral arguments portrayed the Court as appearing likely to hold Section 5 or Section 4(b) unconstitutional.<ref name=\"oral-1\">{{cite news|last=Reilly|first=Ryan J.|title=Voting Rights Act Supreme Court Case: Scalia Condemns The 'Perpetuation Of Racial Entitlement'|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/02/27/voting-rights-act-supreme-court_n_2768942.html|accessdate=13 July 2013|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=27 Feb 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"oral-2\">{{cite news|last=Lengell|first=Sean|title=Scalia \u2018racial\u2019 comment on voting rights law draws fire|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/feb/28/scalia-racial-comment-draws-fire|accessdate=13 July 2013|newspaper=The Washington Times|date=Feb 28, 2013}}</ref> Justice [[Antonin Scalia]] drew criticism from civil rights leaders, after expressing his belief during oral arguments that Congress reauthorized Section 5, not because the legislation was necessary, but because it constituted a \"racial entitlement\" that Congress was unlikely to end.<ref name=\"oral-1\" /><ref name=\"oral-2\" /><ref name=\"oral-3\">{{cite news|last=Goodwin|first=Liz|title=Civil rights leaders outraged over Scalia\u2019s \u2018racial entitlement\u2019 argument|url=https://news.yahoo.com/blogs/ticket/civil-rights-leaders-outraged-over-scalia-racial-entitlement-172338534--election.html|accessdate=13 July 2013|newspaper=Yahoo! News|date=28 Feb 2013}}</ref>\n\nA coalition of [https://ag.ny.gov/sites/default/files/press-releases/2011/ShelbyAmicusBrief.pdf 4 states provided an amicus brief] to the Supreme Court expressing support for Section 5 and noting that the preclearance provision did not impose a burden on them. That coalition was [https://ag.ny.gov/press-release/ag-schneiderman-takes-legal-action-protect-voting-rights-act-against-constitutional led by New York] and included Mississippi, North Carolina and California.\n\n== Opinion of the Supreme Court ==\nThe Supreme Court struck down Section 4(b) as unconstitutional in its June 25, 2013 ruling.<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\" /><ref name=\"THP20130625\">{{cite news|title=Voting Rights Act Section 4 Struck Down By Supreme Court|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/25/voting-rights-act-supreme-court_n_3429810.html|accessdate=7 July 2013|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=25 June 2013|author=Ryan J. Reilly, Mike Sacks and Sabrina Siddiqu}}</ref> The [[majority opinion]] was delivered by Chief Justice [[John Roberts]] joined by Justices [[Antonin Scalia]], [[Anthony Kennedy]], [[Clarence Thomas]], and [[Samuel Alito]].<ref name=\"NBC20130625\" /><ref name=\"rolls back\">{{cite news| url=http://swampland.time.com/2013/06/25/high-court-rolls-back-the-voting-rights-act-of-1965/ |title=High Court Rolls Back the Voting Rights Act of 1965 | work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date=2013-06-25 | accessdate=2013-06-25 | author=Von Drehle, David|authorlink=David Von Drehle}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Barnes|first=Robert|title=Supreme Court stops use of key part of Voting Rights Act|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/supreme-court-stops-use-of-key-part-of-voting-rights-act/2013/06/25/26888528-dda5-11e2-b197-f248b21f94c4_story.html|accessdate=29 June 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=25 June 2013}}</ref> The Court held that Section 4(b) exceeded Congress's power to enforce the Fourteenth and Fifteenth Amendments, reasoning that the coverage formula conflicts with the constitutional principles of [[Federalism in the United States|federalism]] and \"equal sovereignty of the states\" because the disparate treatment of the states is \"based on 40 year-old facts having no logical relationship to the present day\" and thus is not responsive to current needs.<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\" /><ref name=\"oyez\" /> The Court expressed that Congress cannot subject a state to preclearance based simply on past discrimination. It noted that since the coverage formula was last modified in 1975, the country \"has changed, and while any racial discrimination in voting is too much, Congress must ensure that the legislation it passes to remedy that problem speaks to current conditions\".<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\" /><ref name=\"SCOTUSBlogShapiro\">{{cite web|last=Shapiro|first=Ilya|title=Supreme Court recognizes Jim Crow's demise, restores constitutional order|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/?p=165978|publisher=SCOTUSblog|accessdate=5 July 2013|date=25 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|last=Cohen|first=Andrew|title=On Voting Rights, a Decision as Lamentable as Plessy or Dred Scott|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/national/archive/2013/06/on-voting-rights-a-decision-as-lamentable-as-plessy-or-dred-scott/276455/|accessdate=7 July 2013|work=The Atlantic|date=25 June 2013}}</ref> The Court declared that the Fifteenth Amendment \"commands that the right to vote shall not be denied or abridged on account of race or color, and it gives Congress the power to enforce that command. The Amendment is not designed to punish for the past; its purpose is to ensure a better future.\"<ref name=\"NYT20130625\" />\n\nRoberts wrote that the Act was immensely successful \"at redressing racial discrimination and integrating the voting process\u201d and noted that the U.S. has made great progress thanks to the Act.<ref name=\"NBC20130625\" /> But he added: \u201cIf Congress had started from scratch in 2006, it plainly could not have enacted the present coverage formula.\u201d<ref name=\"NBC20130625\">{{cite news|title=Supreme Court strikes down part of Voting Rights Act|url=http://nbcpolitics.nbcnews.com/_news/2013/06/25/19132385-supreme-court-strikes-down-part-of-voting-rights-act?lite|accessdate=27 August 2013|newspaper=NBCNews|date=25 June 2013|author=Pete Williams and Erin McClam}}</ref> According to the Court, \"Regardless of how to look at the record no one can fairly say that it shows anything approaching the 'pervasive,' 'flagrant,' 'widespread,' and 'rampant' discrimination that faced Congress in 1965, and that clearly distinguished the covered jurisdictions from the rest of the nation.\"<ref name=\"NYT20130625\">{{cite news|title=Between the Lines of the Voting Rights Act Opinion|author=Schwartz, John|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/06/25/us/annotated-supreme-court-decision-on-voting-rights-act.html?ref=us&_r=0|newspaper=The New York Times|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=25 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2013/06/opinion-recap-voting-law-in-deep-peril/|title=Open recap: Voting law in deep peril|last=Lyle|first=Denniston|date=June 25, 2013|publisher=[[SCOTUSblog]]|accessdate=June 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Court did not subject Section 4(b) to the \"[[Congressional power of enforcement|congruence and proportionality]]\" standard of review or address whether that standard is the appropriate measure to use when determining the constitutionality of legislation passed pursuant to Section 2 of the Fifteenth Amendment.<ref name=\"Hasen-congruence\">{{cite news|last=Hasen|first=Richard|title=The curious disappearance of Boerne and the future jurisprudence of voting rights and race|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/?p=165958|accessdate=5 August 2013|newspaper=SCOTUSblog|date=25 June 2013}}</ref> The Court also noted the federalism concerns raised by the Section 5 preclearance requirement, but it did not reach the issue of whether Section 5 remains constitutional. However, because the Section 5 preclearance requirement applies only to jurisdictions covered by the Section 4(b) coverage formula, the decision rendered Section 5 inoperable unless Congress enacts a new coverage formula.<ref name=\"plain-english\" /><ref name=\"THP20130625\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|title=The Formula Behind the Voting Rights Act|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/06/23/us/voting-rights-act-map.html|accessdate=8 July 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=22 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nJustice Thomas wrote a [[concurring opinion]] expressing his view that Section 5 is also unconstitutional for the same reasons the Court held Section 4(b) unconstitutional.<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\" /><ref name=\"NYT20130626\">{{cite news|title=Supreme Court Invalidates Key Part of Voting Rights Act|author=Liptak, Adam|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/26/us/supreme-court-ruling.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=26 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nJustice [[Ruth Bader Ginsburg]] wrote a [[dissenting opinion]] that was joined by Justices [[Stephen Breyer]], [[Sonia Sotomayor]], and [[Elana Kagan|Elena Kagan]]. The dissent would have held that Congress had sufficient evidence before it to determine that the coverage formula remained responsive to current needs. The dissent acknowledged that discrimination in voting has decreased in the covered jurisdictions since the Voting Rights Act's enactment, but it attributed much of that decrease to the Act itself, noting that \"[t]hrowing out preclearance when it has worked and is continuing to work to stop discriminatory changes is like throwing away your umbrella in a rainstorm because you are not getting wet.\"<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\" /><ref name=\"oyez\" /><ref name=\"NYT20130625\"/>\n\n==Reaction==\nThe controversial Supreme Court opinion prompted heavy media coverage of reactions from political leaders, activists, and the legal community. President [[Barack Obama]] expressed deep disappointment with the decision and called on Congress \"to pass legislation to ensure every American has equal access to the polls\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Voting Rights Act Section 4 Struck Down By Supreme Court |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/25/obama-voting-rights-act_n_3497124.html|accessdate=5 July 2013 |newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=25 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Jackson|first=David|title=Obama 'disappointed' in court's voting rights decision |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/theoval/2013/06/25/obama-supreme-court-voting-rights-act/2455939|accessdate=5 July 2013|newspaper=USA Today|date=25 June 2013}}</ref> Attorney General [[Eric Holder]] also expressed disappointment with the decision, and he pledged that the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] \"will not hesitate to take swift enforcement action\u2014using every legal tool that remains available to us\u2014against any jurisdiction that seeks to take advantage of the Supreme Court's ruling by hindering eligible citizens' full and free exercise of the franchise\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Reilly |first=Ryan |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/25/eric-holder-voting-rights-act_n_3496909.html|title=Eric Holder Warns Voting Rights Act Decision Could 'Negatively Affect Millions Of Americans'|accessdate=5 July 2013|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=25 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Holder: 'Deeply disappointed' in ruling |url=http://www.cnn.com/video/data/2.0/video/politics/2013/06/25/sot-atw-scotus-voting-rights-holder.cnn.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=5 July 2013|date=25 June 2013}}</ref> On July 25, 2013, Holder announced that the Department of Justice would ask a federal court to subject the formerly covered state of [[Texas]] to preclearance under the \"bail in\" provision contained in Section 3 of the Voting Rights Act, which was unaffected by the Court's decision.<ref>{{cite news |last=Millhiser|first=Ian|title=Justice Department Will Ask Court To Reinstate Voting Rights Act In Texas |url=http://thinkprogress.org/justice/2013/07/25/2354501/breaking-justice-department-will-ask-court-to-reinstate-voting-rights-act-in-texas/?mobile=nc|accessdate=27 July 2013|date=27 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Coyle|first=Marcia|title=DOJ Messes With Texas Over VRA|url=http://www.law.com/jsp/nlj/PubArticleNLJ.jsp?id=1202612526515|accessdate=27 July 2013|newspaper=The National Law Journal|date=25 July 2013|author2=Rugger, Todd}}</ref>\n\nWhen asked whether a polarized Congress could agree on a new coverage formula, Speaker [[John Boehner]] acknowledged the importance of the role of the Voting Rights Act over the previous 40 years and said that he was still reviewing the decision and trying to determine the next steps. Then [[Party leaders of the United States House of Representatives#Job description|House Majority Leader]] [[Eric Cantor]] expressed his hope that Congress would \"put politics aside\" and determine how to ensure that voting rights remain protected.<ref name=congressional-republicans>{{cite news|last=McAuliff|first=Michael|title=John Boehner, Republicans Show No Signs Of Fixing Voting Rights Act |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/26/john-boehner-voting-rights_n_3503714.html|accessdate=5 July 2013 |newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=26 June 2013}}</ref> Representative [[John Lewis (Georgia politician)|John Lewis]], a leader in the civil rights movement who was present when President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] signed the Voting Rights Act into law, said that the decision disregarded the country's history of voting discrimination and that he fears the decision will allow local election officials \"to go back to another period\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Zeleny|first=Jeff|title=John Lewis: Court\u2019s Decision Puts 'Dagger in Heart of Voting Rights Act' |url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2013/06/courts-decision-puts-dagger-in-heart-of-voting-rights-act/|accessdate=5 July 2013|publisher=ABC News|date=25 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=outrage-overdue>{{cite news |last=Mears|first=Bill|title='Outrageous' or overdue?: Court strikes down part of historic voting rights law |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/06/25/politics/scotus-voting-rights|publisher=CNN|accessdate=5 July 2013|author2=Botelho, Greg|date=26 June 2013}}</ref> Representative [[Bob Goodlatte]], Chair of the [[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|House Judiciary Committee]], said that the committee will review new voting data but that he is unsure whether the committee will take any specific action in response to the decision.<ref>{{cite news|last=Killough|first=Ashley|title=Goodlatte unsure if Congress will take up Voting Rights Act|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2013/06/30/goodlatte-unsure-if-congress-will-take-up-voting-rights-act |accessdate=11 July 2013|publisher=CNN|date=30 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=senate-hearings>{{cite news|last=Whitaker|first=Morgan|title=Senate committee moving forward on Voting Rights Act|url=http://tv.msnbc.com/2013/07/10/senate-committee-moving-forward-on-voting-rights-act/|accessdate=11 July 2013|publisher=MSNBC|date=10 July 2013}}</ref> On July 18, 2013, the [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on the Constitution and Civil Justice|House Judiciary Subcommittee on the Constitution and Civil Justice]] held a hearing to discuss how the House should respond to the ruling.<ref>{{cite news|title=Congress divided on voting rights fix |url=http://www.greenvilleonline.com/article/20130719/NEWS/307190007/Congress-divided-voting-rights-fix |accessdate=19 July 2013|newspaper=GreenvilleOnline.com|date=18 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nSenate Majority Leader [[Harry Reid]] said that [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] were concerned with the ruling in light of \"[[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] doing everything they could to suppress voting\" in the 2012 elections, and he stated that the Senate will act to address the decision.<ref>{{cite news |last=Van Dongen|first=Rachel|title=Harry Reid: Senate 'will act' on Voting Rights Act |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/06/voting-rights-act-harry-reid-senate-93344.html|accessdate=5 July 2013 |newspaper=Politico|date=25 June 2013|author2=Everett, Burgess}}</ref> Senator [[Bob Corker]], however, said that he \"cannot imagine\" Congress ever agreeing on the terms of a new coverage formula.<ref name=congressional-republicans /><ref>{{cite news|last=Bendery|first=Jennifer|title=Bob Corker On Voting Rights Act: 'Cannot Imagine' Congress Restoring It |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/25/bob-corker-voting-rights-act_n_3499352.html|accessdate=5 July 2013 |newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=25 July 2013}}</ref> The [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Senate Judiciary Committee]] began to hold hearings on July 17, 2013 to discuss how to respond to the decision.<ref name=senate-hearings /><ref>{{cite news|last=Melber|first=Ari|title=Senate tackles Voting Rights Act |url=http://tv.msnbc.com/2013/07/17/senate-tackles-voting-rights-act/|accessdate=18 July 2013 |publisher=MSNBC|date=17 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt the state level, Texas and [[Mississippi]] officials pledged within hours of the decision to enforce voter ID laws that had not been precleared by the Attorney General.<ref>{{cite news|last=Applewhite|first=Scott|title=For Republicans, no easy answers on Voting Rights Act |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-250_162-57592414/for-republicans-no-easy-answers-on-voting-rights-act |accessdate=5 July 2013|publisher=CBS News|date=5 July 2013}}</ref> [[Florida]] Secretary of State Ken Detzner said it made no sense for five Florida counties to be subjected to preclearance based on decades-old voting rights data and that the decision will save the state money.<ref>{{cite news|last=Klas|first=Mary Ellen|title=Court blocks application of Voting Rights Act in Florida, unless Congress updates rules |url=http://miamiherald.typepad.com/nakedpolitics/2013/06/court-blocks-application-of-voting-rights-act-in-florida-unless-congress-updates-rules.html |accessdate=5 July 2013|newspaper=Miami Herald|date=25 June 2013}}</ref> [[New York (state)|New York]] Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] found the decision deeply troubling and called upon Congress to pass a new coverage formula.<ref>{{cite news |last=Katz|first=Celeste|title=SCOTUS And The Voting Rights Act, Part 5: Ruling 'Deeply Troubling', Gov. Cuomo Says|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/2013/06/scotus-and-the-voting-rights-act-part-5-ruling-deeply-troubling-gov-cuomo-says |accessdate=5 July 2013|newspaper= New York Daily News|date=25 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nIlya Shapiro of the [[Cato Institute]] said that the Supreme Court's decision \"restore[d] the constitutional order, the status quo ante the temporary Sections 4/5, because there is no longer systemic racial disenfranchisement, or at the very least in the covered jurisdictions\".<ref name=\"SCOTUSBlogShapiro\" /> In contrast, Jon Greenbaum, chief counsel of the [[Lawyers' Committee for Civil Rights Under Law]], said that because of the decision, \"[m]inority voters in places with a record of discrimination are now at greater risk of being disenfranchised than they have been in decades\" and that their only recourse will be to pursue expensive litigation.<ref>{{cite news|last=De Vogue|first=Ariane|title=Supreme Court Strikes Down Key Part of Voting Rights Act|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/supreme-court-strikes-portion-voting-rights-act/story?id=19459258|accessdate=5 July 2013|publisher=ABC News|date=25 June 2013}}</ref> [[Penda Hair]], co-director of national racial justice organization [[Advancement Project]], spoke along similar lines, saying, \"The Supreme Court's ruling rolls back legislation that courageous Americans fought so hard for, even giving their lives in many cases, to ensure that all citizens can participate in our democracy. Today's decision threatens the promise of equal access to the ballot \u2013 especially when the majority of voters of color who voted last year, 65.8 percent, live in states covered by the Section 4 formula.\"<ref>[http://www.advancementproject.org/news/entry/scotus-removes-critical-protection-for-voters-of-color \"SCOTUS Removes Critical Protection for Voters of Color\"], ''Advancement Project'', June 25, 2013</ref>\n\nAn investigation by [[ProPublica]] in October 2017 revealed that Chief Justice John Roberts used erroneous data in the ruling.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/supreme-court-errors-are-not-hard-to-find|title=It's a Fact: Supreme Court Errors Aren't Hard to Find |date=2017-10-17|website=ProPublica|language=en-us|first=Ryan |last=Gabrielson|accessdate=2017-10-17}}</ref> Roberts claimed that the registration gap between blacks and whites had shrunk dramatically in southern states since the Civil Rights Act of 1965, thus calling into question why six southern states were subject to stringent oversight.<ref name=\":3\" /> Roberts included Hispanics into his numbers for whites, including even those who could not register to vote because they were not U.S. citizens, thereby making the newly \"white\" registration rate lower than what it would have been.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Impact==\nSince the ruling, several states once covered under preclearance have passed laws that removed provisions such as online voting registration, early voting, \"Souls to the Polls\" Sunday voting, same-day registration, and pre-registration for teens about to turn 18. The ruling has also resulted in some states implementing voter identification laws and becoming more aggressive in expunging allegedly ineligible voters from registration rolls.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fuller|first1=Jaime|title=How has voting changed since Shelby County v. Holder?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2014/07/07/how-has-voting-changed-since-shelby-county-v-holder/|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=July 7, 2014}}</ref> States that have changed their voting policies post-Shelby include both jurisdictions that were previously required to undergo federal preclearance, as well as some that were not covered, including Alabama, Arizona, Arkansas, North Carolina, Ohio, Wisconsin and Texas. According to the Brennan Center for Justice, the states most likely to enact voting restrictions were states with the highest African-American turnout in the 2008 election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brennancenter.org/analysis/election-2016-restrictive-voting-laws-numbers|title=Election 2016: Restrictive Voting Laws by the Numbers |publisher=Brennan Center for Justice |language=en|accessdate=2018-12-22}}</ref>\n\nThree years after the ruling, 868 polling places had been closed down.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomsbury.com/us/one-person-no-vote-9781635571387/|title=One Person, No Vote|last=Anderson|first=Carol|date=2018|website=www.bloomsbury.com|accessdate=2018-12-22|quote=Because of ''Shelby County v. Holder'', by 2016, there were 868 fewer precincts in Section 5 jurisdictions.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2016/11/4/13501120/vote-polling-places-election-2016|title=Southern states have closed down at least 868 polling places for the 2016 election|last=Lopez|first=German|date=2016-11-04|website=Vox|accessdate=2018-12-22}}</ref> Five years after the ruling, nearly a thousand polling places had been closed in the country, with many of the closed polling places in predominantly African-American counties. Research shows that the changing of voter locations and reduction in voting locations can reduce voter turnout.<ref name=\":4\"/> A 2018 report by the [[United States Commission on Civil Rights|U.S. Commission on Civil Rights]] (a bipartisan, independent commission of the United States federal government) found that there had been a growth in discriminatory laws making it harder for minorities to vote. The commission found that at least 23 states enacted restrictive voter laws, such as closures of polling places, cuts to early voting, purges of voter rolls and imposition of strict voter ID laws. The commission chair said people \"continue to suffer significant, and profoundly unequal, limitations on their ability to vote&nbsp;... That stark reality denigrates our democracy and diminishes our ideals. This level of ongoing discrimination confirms what was true before 1965, when the Voting Rights Act became law, and has remained true since 1965: Americans need strong and effective federal protections to guarantee that ours is a real democracy.\"<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" />\n\nA 2017 study in the ''[[American Journal of Political Science]]'' by Boston University political scientist Sophie Schuit\u00a0and Harvard University political scientist Jon C. Rogowski found that the preclearance requirement in the Voting Rights Act led to greater representation of Black interests, and this effect persisted long after the passage of the Voting Rights Act. The authors of the study note that this finding is contrary to the \"majority's opinion in ''Shelby County v. Holder'' that 'things have changed' and that the issues addressed by the VRA are 'decades\u2010old problems'. To the contrary, preclearance under the VRA appeared to substantially increase Black representation in the contemporary era.\"<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite journal|last=Schuit|first=Sophie|last2=Rogowski|first2=Jon C.|date=2017|title=Race, Representation, and the Voting Rights Act|journal=American Journal of Political Science|language=en|volume=61|issue=3|pages=513\u2013526|doi=10.1111/ajps.12284|issn=1540-5907}}</ref>\n\nA 2019 study in the ''American Economic Journal'' found that preclearance substantially increased turnout among minorities, even as far as to 2012 (the year prior to the Supreme Court ruling ending preclearance).<ref name=\":9\" /> The study estimates that preclearance led to an increase in minority turnout of 17 percentage points.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nVirtually all restrictions on voting subsequent to the ruling were by Republicans.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/03/us/politics/voting-suppression-elections.html|title='They Don't Really Want Us to Vote': How Republicans Made it Harder| first1=Danny |last1=Hakim |first2=Michael |last2=Wines|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=3 November 2018|accessdate=2018-11-04|language=en}}</ref> Numerous strict voter ID laws have been passed in states that required preclearance under the Civil Rights Act. Such laws were passed for the stated reason of preventing vote fraud; however, there is no evidence of widespread voter fraud, and critics say these laws are intended to make it harder for minorities to vote.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://bostonreview.net/politics/ariel-white-voter-id-laws|title=Voter Discrimination Starts Well Before Election Day|last=White|first=Ariel|date=2016-10-31|website=Boston Review|language=en|accessdate=2018-12-22}}</ref> According to MIT political scientist Ariel White, there is evidence that voter ID laws have a disparate impact on minority voting whereas there is little evidence that voter-ID laws prevent voter fraud.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n===Alabama===\nAfter ''Shelby'', Alabama Republicans drew a new legislative apportionment map of the state that some{{who|date=March 2019}} contend is illegal. Democrats said that the new map packs African-American voters into too few voting districts and is an effort to hamper the power of the largely Democratic voting base.<ref name=Hananel_Sam>{{cite news|last1=Hananel|first1=Sam|title=Supreme Court To Hear Alabama Redistricting Challenge|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/06/02/supreme-court-alabama-redistricting_n_5431345.html|work=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=2 July 2015|date=June 6, 2014|quote=The U.S. Supreme Court cases are ''Alabama Legislative Black Caucus v. State of Alabama'', 13-895, and ''Alabama Democratic Conference v. Alabama'', 13-1138.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the Supreme Court said it would hear appeals from the Alabama Legislative Black Caucus regarding the redistricting.<ref name=Hananel_Sam />\n\n===Arizona===\nIn an opinion issued by Arizona's attorney general in 2013, Arizona residents who registered to vote using forms provided by the federal government must also provide documentation proving their citizenship, or their registration will be labeled invalid. Attorney General Tom Horne said those who registered using federal registration could vote in federal elections, but not state and local elections without showing proof of citizenship. The attorney general also held that these same registrants will not be able to sign petitions for candidates or ballot initiatives.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilson|first1=Reid|title=Arizona law may restrict voting in local elections |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/govbeat/wp/2013/10/09/arizona-law-may-restrict-voting-in-local-elections/|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=October 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===North Carolina===\nShortly after the Shelby ruling, North Carolina [[Pat McCrory|Gov. Pat McCrory]] signed into law H.B. 589, which terminated valid out-of-precinct voting, same-day registration during the early voting period, and pre-registration for teenagers about to turn 18, while also enacting a voter ID law. Opponents criticized this law as adversely affecting minority voters.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Baggett|first1=Leela|title=North Carolina H.B. 589: Putting Up Barriers For Voters Who Move |url=http://www.projectvote.org/blog/2013/08/north-carolinas-h-b-589-putting-up-barriers-for-voters-who-move/|work=Project Vote Blog|accessdate=July 2, 2015|date=August 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe law was challenged, on behalf of the North Carolina State Conference of the NAACP, by a lawsuit filed by Advancement Project, pro bono counsel [[Kirkland & Ellis]], and North Carolina attorneys Adam Stein and Irv Joyner. The suit alleged that the law violates Section 2 of the Voting Rights Act, as well as the 14th and 15th Amendments of the U.S. Constitution.<ref>{{cite web|title=North Carolina State Conference of the NAACP v. McCrory |url=http://www.advancementproject.org/pages/north-carolina-vpp|publisher=Advancement Project|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn July 29, 2016, a three-judge panel of the [[Fourth Circuit Court of Appeals]] reversed a trial court decision in a number of consolidated actions, finding that the new voting provisions targeted African Americans \"with almost surgical precision\" and that the legislators had acted with \"discriminatory intent\" in enacting strict election rules; the Court struck down the law's photo ID requirement and changes to early voting, preregistration, same-day registration and out-of-district voting.<ref>{{cite news |author=Ann E. Marimow |title=Appeals court strikes down North Carolina's voter-ID law |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/appeals-court-strikes-down-north-carolinas-voter-id-law/2016/07/29/810b5844-4f72-11e6-aa14-e0c1087f7583_story.html |work=Washington Post |date=July 29, 2016 |accessdate=2016-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/north-carolina-voter-id_us_579b8862e4b08a8e8b5de534|title=North Carolina Voter ID Law Targeted African-Americans, Appeals Court Rules|author1=Julia Harte|author2=Andy Sullivan|date=July 29, 2016|newspaper=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n\n===North Dakota===\nAs of October 10, 2018, an act of North Dakota was upheld by the United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit<ref name=North_Dakota_CourtRuling2018>https://ecf.ca8.uscourts.gov/opndir/18/09/181725P.pdf</ref> which requires individuals who vote to have a voter ID which has their name, street address, and date of birth. At the time the state's Native reservations did not generally have street addresses, only post boxes for residents; there was concern that this provision would disproportionately affect Native voting,<ref>https://www.wbur.org/hereandnow/2018/10/23/north-dakota-voter-id-law-native-americans</ref> and speculation that it was drafted with that as a primary goal.<ref>https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/native-americans-fighting-back-against-north-dakota-voter-id-law-n926326</ref>\n\nDissenters Justices Ginsburg and Kagan said, \"The risk of [[voter confusion]] appears severe here because the injunction against requiring residential-address identification was in force during the primary election and because the Secretary of State\u2019s website announced for months the ID requirements as they existed under that injunction.\"{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Ohio===\nIn February 2014, the Ohio House approved a bill that eliminated the so-called \"Golden Week\" during which Ohio voters could register and vote on the same day. The bill also cut six days from Ohio's early voting period. In a separate bill, the House made it easier for registrars to reject absentee ballots for missing information. This bill ends a program that mailed absentee ballots to all registered voters. Under the new law, Ohio's secretary of state would have to get lawmaker approval to mail these absentee ballots.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Higgs |first1=Robert |title=Kasich signs voting bills that end Golden Week and limit distribution of absentee ballots |url=http://www.cleveland.com/open/index.ssf/2014/02/kasich_signs_voting_bills_that.html|accessdate=2 July 2015 |work=www.cleveland.com|publisher=Northeast Ohio Media Group Columbus|date=February 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Texas===\nWhile its voter ID law was passed in 2011, Texas did not enact the law until 2013 after the ''Shelby'' ruling, when the state was no longer subject to federal preclearance for changes to its voting laws. Under the law, Texas voters must show a photo ID to vote. While there are some exemptions, such as for voters with disabilities, most are required to produce a Texas driver's license or state ID card. Other forms of acceptable ID include concealed handgun licenses, military ID, U.S. citizenship papers with photo and a U.S. passport.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Langford|first1=Terri|title=Criminal Appeals Court Judge Files Suit Over Voter ID |url=http://www.texastribune.org/2014/10/02/criminal-appeals-court-judge-files-voter-id-lawsui/|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=The Texas Tribune|date=October 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIf the voter does not possess one of the forms of acceptable photo ID and cannot reasonably obtain one, the voter may present one of the following, after which he or she must execute a Reasonable Impediment Declaration:<ref>http://www.sos.state.tx.us/elections/forms/pol-sub/reasonable-impediment-declaration.pdf</ref> a copy or original of a government document that shows the voter's name and an address, including the voter's voter registration certificate; a current utility bill; a bank statement; a government check; a paycheck; or (a) a certified domestic (from a U.S. state or territory) birth certificate or (b) a document confirming birth admissible in a court of law which establishes the voter's identity (which may include a foreign birth document).<ref>http://www.votetexas.gov/register-to-vote/need-id.html|Required Identification for Voting in Person</ref>\n\nCritics of the law{{who|date=September 2018}} charge that it is unconstitutional. They also say that it will bar legitimate voters from voting and discourage citizens. Examples of problems under the new law involved public figures: Texas judge, Sandra Watts, was unable to vote because the name on her photo ID did not match the name on the voter rolls. Also, State Senator Wendy Davis and then-Attorney General Greg Abbott were delayed in voting under the new law. They were all able to vote after signing affidavits attesting that they were who they claimed to be.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lyman|first1=Rick|title=Texas' Stringent Voter ID Law Makes a Dent at Polls |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/07/us/politics/texas-stringent-voter-id-law-makes-a-dent-at-polls.html|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=The New York Times|date=November 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Wisconsin===\nIn 2014, the American Civil Liberties Union and the Advancement Project filed a petition asking the Supreme Court to block Wisconsin's voter ID law, charging the measure would disproportionately affect voters of color.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilson|first1=Reid|title=Voting rights advocates want Supreme Court to block Wisconsin voter ID law|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/govbeat/wp/2014/10/02/voting-rights-advocates-want-supreme-court-to-block-wisconsin-voter-id-law/|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=October 2, 2014}}</ref> Challenging the law under Section 2 of the Voting Rights Act and the U.S. Constitution, Advancement Project litigated on behalf of the League of United Latin American Citizens of Wisconsin, Cross Lutheran Church, Wisconsin League of Young Voters Education Fund, and the Milwaukee Area Labor Council of the AFL-CIO.<ref name=\"Advancement Project20141009\">{{cite web|last1=Gordy|first1=Cynthia|title=Wisconsin Voter ID Law Halted, as Supreme Court Blocks Appeals Court Order|url=http://www.advancementproject.org/news/entry/wisconsin-voter-id-law-halted-as-supreme-court-blocks-appeals-court-order|publisher=Advancement Project|accessdate=2 July 2015|date=October 9, 2014}}</ref> Advancement Project claimed that Wisconsin's voter ID law, enacted in 2012, is \"part of a broader attack on the right to vote\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Farmer|first1=Jennifer|title=Advocates To Challenge Wisconsin's Anti-Voting Law In Federal Court|url=http://www.advancementproject.org/news/entry/advocates-to-challenge-wisconsins-anti-voting-law-in-federal-court|publisher=Advancement Project|accessdate=2 July 2015|date=October 30, 2014}}</ref> On October 9, 2014, the U.S. Supreme Court issued an emergency stay in this case, blocking a Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals order to implement Wisconsin\u2019s voter ID law and enabling registration under previous rules for the fall of 2014 elections. It has yet to rule on the provisions of Wisconsin's law.<ref name=\"Advancement Project20141009\" />\n\n== Legislative responses ==\nOn January 16, 2014, a bipartisan group of members of Congress, consisting of Representatives [[Jim Sensenbrenner]] and [[John Conyers]] and Senator [[Patrick Leahy]], introduced H.R.3899/S.R.1945,<ref name=\"20140428VRAFORTODAY\">{{cite web|last1=Lewis|first1=Tyler|title=Bill Summary: Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2014|url=http://vrafortoday.org/?attachment_id=252|publisher=VRA for Today|accessdate=4 July 2015|date=April 28, 2014|quote=See also http://vrafortoday.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/2014-04-07-VRAA-Bill-Summary_c4.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150707095901/http://vrafortoday.org/?attachment_id=252|archivedate=7 July 2015}}</ref> entitled the Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2014. The bill was introduced to strengthen the Voting Rights Act of 1965 (VRA) and vital protections of it following the 2013 Supreme Court's decision in ''Shelby County v. Holder''.<ref name=\"TheNation20150116\" /> The proposed Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2014 consists of five components:<ref name=\"20140428VRAFORTODAY\" /><ref name=\"TheNation20150116\">{{cite news |last1=Berman |first1=Ari |title=Members of Congress Introduce a New Fix for the Voting Rights Act |url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/177962/members-congress-introduce-new-fix-voting-rights-act#|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=[[The Nation]]|date=January 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n# Based on empirical conditions and current data there is a new coverage formula for Section 4 based on a rolling calendar, updated with a current fifteen-year time period to exempt states who are no longer discriminating or add new ones who are. The last part is designed to create a deterrent against future voting rights violations. Under the new formula states with five violations of federal law to their voting changes over the past fifteen years will have to submit future election changes for federal approval. Local jurisdictions would be covered if they commit three or more violations or have one violation and \"persistent, extremely low minority turnout\" over the past fifteen years. While Voter ID laws can still be blocked by the Department of Justice in the new states covered under Section 4, objections to voter ID laws by the department will not count as a new violation.\n# Section 3 of the bill makes it possible that a court may order jurisdictions not covered by Section 4 to have future changes to its election laws preapproved by the federal government after plaintiffs file a corresponding application with the court. Plaintiffs have to show evidence of intentional voting discrimination to enable such a bail-in. Any violation of the VRA or of federal voting rights law\u2014whether intentional or not\u2014can be under the new section 3 proposal grounds for a bail-in, but court objections to voter ID laws that are not found to be intentionally discriminatory cannot be used as grounds for \"bail-in\" under Section 3.\n# Jurisdictions in all U.S. states have to provide notice in the local media and online of any election procedures related to redistricting, changes within 180 days of a federal election and the moving of a polling place. Citizens can thus easier identify potentially harmful voting changes in states not subject to Sections 4 and 5 of the VRA.\n# Plaintiffs seeking a preliminary injunction against a potentially discriminatory voting law must only show that the hardship to them outweighs the hardship to the state if a law is blocked in court pending a full trial.\n# Affirming the attorney general's authority to send federal observers in states subject to Section 4 to monitor elections in these states the proposal expands the attorney general's authority to send observers to jurisdictions with a history of discriminating against language minority groups.\n\nAs of June 2014 the proposed Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2014 was in limbo because there is no widespread support to amend the Voting Rights Act as it was by its re-authorization in 2006 by Congress.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fuller|first1=Jaime|title=Republicans used to unanimously back the Voting Rights Act. Not any more |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2014/06/26/republicans-used-to-unanimously-back-voting-rights-act-not-any-more/ |accessdate=2 July 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=June 26, 2014}}</ref> Both the House and Senate versions of the bill ultimately died in their respective Judiciary Committees.<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3899 (113th): Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2014|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr3899|publisher=[[GovTrack]]|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=S. 1945 (113th): Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2014| url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/s1945|publisher=[[GovTrack]]|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref> The House introduced the Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2015 the following year.<ref>{{cite web|title=All Bill Information (Except Text) for H.R. 885 \u2013 Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2015 |url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/885/all-info|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|accessdate=6 October 2015|date=2015-03-16}}</ref> It was referred to the House Judiciary Committee on the day it was introduced, but did not move past the committee stage.<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R. 885 (114th): Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2015|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr885|publisher=[[GovTrack]]|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref> The Voting Rights Advancement Act of 2015 (H.R. 2867), a similar measure to the Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2015, was introduced on June 24, 2015, but died with the end of the [[114th United States Congress]].<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R. 2867 (114th): Voting Rights Advancement Act of 2015|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr2867|website=[[GovTrack]]|publisher=[[GovTrack]]|accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> The most recent legislative attempt, the Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2017 (H.R. 3239), was introduced on July 13, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3239: Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2017|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/115/hr3239|website=[[GovTrack]]|accessdate=October 13, 2017}}</ref> and again referred to the House Judiciary Committee.<ref>{{cite web|title=All Information (Except Text) for H.R.3239 \u2013 Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2017|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-bill/3239/all-info|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|accessdate=13 October 2017|date=2017-08-03}}</ref>\n\nNew York Senator [[Kirsten Gillibrand]] proposed to make online voter registration universal. Under her proposal states with existing online access would expand their system beyond those with state-issued IDs to allow more young people, seniors, minorities and the poor access and update their own voter records online. To ensure security, online systems will verify voter's eligibility by checking each person's personal information, like date of birth, Social Security, and address.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Jill Castellano and Reuven Blau|title=Sen. Kirsten Gillibrand plans to introduce legislation to allow voters to register online |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/sen-kristen-gillibrand-expand-online-voter-registration-article-1.1839665 |accessdate=2 July 2015|work=The New York Daily News|date=June 22, 2014}}</ref> According to the [[Brennan Center for Justice]] at New York University Law School in 2014 several states (California, Colorado, Hawaii, Illinois, Louisiana, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Mississippi, Nebraska, Oklahoma, South Carolina, Utah) and Washington, D.C. passed laws improving voter access, while laws restricting voter access was only passed by a minority of states in 2014. Introduced and pending legislation to expand and improve access to registration and voting include as of December 2014 electronic transfer of voter registration information, online registration, portability i.e. the possibility to move a voter's registration with her when she moves to a new address within the same county or state, fail-safe protections, easier registration and voting for students, people with disabilities, military members and for voters who speak a language other than English as well as expansion of opportunities for voting registration and for early in-person voting.<ref>{{cite web|title=Voting Laws Roundup 2014 |url=http://www.brennancenter.org/analysis/voting-laws-roundup-2014|publisher=Brennan Center for Justice |accessdate=2 July 2015|date=December 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, congressional Democrats introduced the Voting Rights Advancement Act, which would restore the Voting Rights Act's preclearance provision, requiring certain jurisdictions to secure federal approval before enacting voting changes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/431693-democrats-introduce-bill-to-strengthen-voting-rights-act|title=Dems introduce bills to restore Voting Rights Act provision|last=Bowden|first=John|date=2019-02-26|website=The Hill|language=en|accessdate=2019-06-24}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{caselaw source\n | case = ''Shelby County v. Holder'', {{Ussc|570|529|2013|el=no}}\n | courtlistener =\n | googlescholar = https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=1305449212751290785\n | justia =\n | oyez =https://www.oyez.org/cases/2012/12-96\n | other_source1 = Supreme Court (slip opinion)\n | other_url1 =https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/12pdf/12-96_6k47.pdf\n}}\n\n[[Category:United States elections case law]]\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases]]\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases of the Roberts Court]]\n[[Category:2013 in United States case law]]\n[[Category:Shelby County, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Legal history of Alabama]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2013 landmark United States Supreme Court case}}\n{{Infobox SCOTUS case\n |Litigants=Shelby County v. Holder\n |ArgueDate=February 27\n |ArgueYear=2013\n |DecideDate=June 25\n |DecideYear=2013\n |FullName=[[Shelby County, Alabama]], Petitioner v. [[Eric Holder|Eric H. Holder, Jr.]], [[United States Attorney General|Attorney General]], et al.\n |USVol=570\n |USPage=529\n |Docket=12-96\n |OralArgument=https://www.oyez.org/cases/2010-2019/2012/2012_12_96/argument\n |ParallelCitations=133 S. Ct. 2612; 186 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 651\n |Prior=Petition denied, 811 [[F. Supp. 2d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infdco20110922a91 424] ([[United States District Court for the District of Columbia|D.D.C.]] 2011); decision affirmed, 679 [[F.3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20120518150 848] ([[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit|D.C. Cir.]] 2012); [[Certiorari|cert]]. granted, {{ussc|568|1006|2012|el=no}}.\n |Subsequent=Remanded, 541 [[F. App'x]] 1 (D.C. Cir. 2013); motion for attorneys' fees denied, 43 [[F. Supp. 3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infdco20140529d46 47] (D.D.C. 2014), affirmed sub. nom., ''Shelby County v. Lynch'', 799 [[F.3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20150901202 1173] (D.C. Cir. 2015); cert. denied, 136 S. Ct. 981 (2016).\n |Holding=Section 4(b) of the [[Voting Rights Act of 1965]] is unconstitutional.\n |Majority=Roberts\n |JoinMajority=Scalia, Kennedy, Thomas, Alito\n |Concurrence=Thomas\n |Dissent=Ginsburg\n |JoinDissent=Breyer, Sotomayor, Kagan\n |LawsApplied=[[Fifteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. amend. XV]]; [[Voting Rights Act of 1965]]\n}}\n\n'''''Shelby County v. Holder''''', 570 U.S. 529 (2013), is a [[list of landmark court decisions in the United States|landmark]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Kealing|first=Jonathan|title=U.S. Supreme Court strikes down key provision of Voting Rights Act|url=http://www.pri.org/stories/politics-society/keywords/stories/politics-society/government/u-s-supreme-court-strikes-down-key-provision-of-voting-rights-act-14209.html|publisher=Public Radio International|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref> [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] case regarding the constitutionality of two provisions of the [[Voting Rights Act of 1965]]: Section 5, which requires certain states and local governments to obtain federal preclearance before implementing any changes to their voting laws or practices; and Section 4(b), which contains the coverage formula that determines which jurisdictions are subjected to preclearance based on their histories of discrimination in voting.<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\">{{ussc|name=Shelby County v. Holder|volume=570|page=529|pin=|year=2013}}.</ref><ref name=\"oyez\">{{cite web|title=SHELBY COUNTY v. HOLDER|publisher=The Oyez Project at IIT Chicago-Kent College of Law|url=https://www.oyez.org/cases/2010-2019/2012/2012_12_96|accessdate=7 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 25, 2013, the Court ruled by a 5-to-4 vote that Section 4(b) is unconstitutional because the coverage formula is based on data over 40 years old, making it no longer responsive to current needs and therefore an impermissible burden on the constitutional principles of [[federalism]] and equal sovereignty of the states.<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\" /><ref name=\"oyez\" /> The Court did not strike down Section 5, but without Section 4(b), no jurisdiction will be subject to Section 5 preclearance unless Congress enacts a new coverage formula.<ref name=\"plain-english\">{{cite web |url= http://www.scotusblog.com/2013/06/details-on-shelby-county-v-holder-in-plain-english |title= Amy Howe, Details on Shelby County v. Holder: In Plain English (Case 12-399) |publisher= SCOTUSblog |date=2013-06-25 |accessdate=June 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nSome critics have said that the ruling has made it easier for state officials to make it harder for Black and other racio-ethnic minority voters to vote.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.pewtrusts.org/research-and-analysis/blogs/stateline/2018/09/04/polling-places-remain-a-target-ahead-of-november-elections|title=Polling Place Politics|website=www.pewtrusts.org|accessdate=2018-09-05}}</ref> Research shows that preclearance led to increases in minority congressional representation and increases in minority turnout.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Ang|first=Desmond|date=2019|title=Do 40-Year-Old Facts Still Matter? Long-Run Effects of Federal Oversight under the Voting Rights Act|url=https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/app.20170572|journal=American Economic Journal: Applied Economics|language=en|volume=11|issue=3|pages=1\u201353|doi=10.1257/app.20170572|issn=1945-7782|via=|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\":10\" /> Five years after the ruling, nearly 1,000 polling places had been closed in the U.S., with many of the closed polling places in predominantly African-American counties. Research shows that the changing of voter locations and reduction in voting locations can reduce voter turnout.<ref name=\":4\" /> There were also cuts to early voting, purges of voter rolls and imposition of strict voter ID laws.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/09/12/politics/voting-rights-federal-commission-election/index.html|title=Discriminatory voter laws have surged in last 5 years, federal commission finds|date=2018|website=CNN}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usccr.gov/pubs/2018/Minority_Voting_Access_2018.pdf|title=Assessment of Minority Voting Rights Access|date=2018|website=U.S. Commission on Civil Rights}}</ref> Virtually all restrictions on voting subsequent to the ruling were by Republicans.<ref name=\":7 />\n\n== Background ==\n[[United States Congress|Congress]] enacted the [[Voting Rights Act of 1965]] to address entrenched racial discrimination in voting, \"an insidious and pervasive evil which had been perpetuated in certain parts of our country through unremitting and ingenious defiance of the Constitution\".<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\" /> Section 5 of the Act contains a \"preclearance\" requirement that requires certain states and local governments to obtain a determination by the [[United States Attorney General]] or a three-judge panel of the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia]] that changes to their voting laws or practices do not \"deny or abridge the right to vote on account of race, color, or membership in a language minority group\", before those changes may be enforced.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Section 5 of the Voting Rights Act|url=http://www.justice.gov/crt/about/vot/sec_5/about.php|work=DOJ Civil Rights Division|publisher=United States Department of Justice|accessdate=7 July 2013}}</ref> Section 4(b) contains the coverage formula that determines which states and local governments are subject to preclearance under Section 5. The formula covers jurisdictions that, as of November 1964, November 1968, or November 1972, maintained a prohibited \"test or device\" as a condition of registering to vote or voting and had a voting-age population of which less than 50 percent either were registered to vote or actually voted in that year's presidential election.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title=Section 4 of the Voting Rights Act|url=http://www.justice.gov/crt/about/vot/misc/sec_4.php|work=DOJ Civil Rights Division|publisher=United States Department of Justice|accessdate=7 July 2013|ref=name=Section4DOJ}}</ref> Section 4(a) allows covered jurisdictions that have made sufficient progress in ending discriminatory voting practices to \"bail out\" of the preclearance requirement.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] upheld the preclearance requirement and coverage formula as constitutional [[Congressional power of enforcement|enforcement legislation]] under Section 2 of the [[Fifteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifteenth Amendment]] in ''[[South Carolina v. Katzenbach]]'' (1966).<ref>[https://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/historics/USSC_CR_0383_0301_ZO.html ''South Carolina v. Katzenbach''], 383 U.S. 301 (1966).</ref> The preclearance requirement initially was set to expire five years after enactment, but amendments to the Act in 1970, 1975, and 1982 reauthorized Section 5; the 1970 and 1975 amendments also updated the coverage formula.<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\" /><ref name=\"Democracy\">{{cite book|last=Issacharoff|first=Samuel|title=The Law of Democracy: Legal Structure of the Political Process|year=2012|publisher=Foundation Press|isbn=978-1599419350|edition=4th|author2=Karlan, Pamela S. |author3=Pildes, Richard H.}}</ref>{{rp|571}} The Supreme Court upheld these reauthorizations as constitutional in ''Georgia v. United States'' (1973),<ref>{{ussc|name=Georgia v. United States|link=|volume=411|page=526|pin=|year=1973}}.</ref> ''City of Rome v. United States'' (1980),<ref>{{ussc|name=Rome v. United States|link=|volume=446|page=156|pin=|year=1980}}.</ref> and ''Lopez v. Monterey County'' (1999).<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\" />{{rp|5}}<ref>{{ussc|name=Lopez v. Monterey County|link=|volume=525|page=266|pin=|year=1999}}.</ref> In 2006, Congress reauthorized Section 5 for an additional 25 years, but it did not change the coverage formula from the 1975 version.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nShortly after the 2006 reauthorization, a [[Texas]] utility district sought to bail out from Section 5 preclearance and, in the alternative, challenged the constitutionality of Section 5. The Supreme Court ruled unanimously in ''[[Northwest Austin Municipal Utility District No. 1 v. Holder]]'' that government entities that did not register voters, such as the utility district, had the right to file suit to bail out of coverage. Because this decision resolved the issue, the Court invoked [[constitutional avoidance]] and declined to address the constitutionality of Section 5. Justice Thomas dissented from this portion of the opinion and would have declared Section 5 unconstitutional.<ref>[https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/08pdf/08-322.pdf ''Northwest Austin Municipal Utility District No. 1 v. Holder''], 557 U.S. 193 (2009).</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n=== District Court ===\n[[Shelby County, Alabama|Shelby County]], in the covered jurisdiction of [[Alabama]], sued the [[United States Attorney General|U.S. Attorney General]] in the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia|U.S. District Court for D.C.]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], seeking a [[declaratory judgment]] that sections 4(b) and 5 are [[Facial challenge|facially unconstitutional]] and a permanent [[injunction]] against their enforcement. On September 21, 2011, Judge [[John D. Bates]] upheld the provisions, finding that the evidence before Congress in 2006 was sufficient to justify reauthorizing Section 5 and continuing Section 4(b)'s coverage formula.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Shelby County v. Holder |vol=811 |reporter=F. Supp. 2d |opinion=424 |pinpoint= |court=[[D.D.C.]] |date=2011 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infdco20110922a91 |accessdate=2018-09-02 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nArguing before Judge Bates included [http://blog.al.com/sweethome/2011/02/shelby_county_voting_rights_ca_2.html Kristen Clarke], who argued that it was reasonable for Congress to \"stay the course\" in renewing Section 5 of the Voting Rights Act in order to root out discrimination. Bert Rein, a lawyer for Shelby County, [http://blog.al.com/sweethome/2011/02/shelby_county_voting_rights_ca_2.html argued] that the environment in the country was \"totally different\" when Section 5 was first enacted.\n\n=== Court of Appeals ===\nOn May 18, 2012, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit|U.S. Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit]] affirmed the decision of the District Court upholding the constitutionality of Section 4(b) and Section 5. After surveying the evidence in the Congressional record associated with the 2006 reauthorization of Section 5, the appellate court accepted Congress's conclusion that Section 2 litigation remained inadequate in the covered jurisdictions to protect the rights of minority voters, that Section 5 was therefore still justified, and that the coverage formula continued to pass constitutional muster.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Shelby County v. Holder |vol=679 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=848 |pinpoint= |court=[[D.C. Cir.]] |date=2012 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20120518150 |accessdate=2018-09-02 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n=== Supreme Court ===\nThe Supreme Court granted ''[[writ of certiorari|certiorari]]'' to hear the case on the limited question of \"whether Congress' decision in 2006 to reauthorize Section 5 of the Voting Rights Act under the pre-existing coverage formula of Section 4(b) of the Voting Rights Act exceeded its authority under the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth]] and [[Fifteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifteenth Amendments]] and thus violated the [[Tenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Tenth Amendment]] and [[Article IV of the United States Constitution]].\"<ref>[https://www.supremecourt.gov/orders/courtorders/110912zr_d18e.pdf Certiorari granted, November 9, 2012]</ref> The Supreme Court heard oral arguments on February 27, 2013.<ref>[https://www.supremecourt.gov/oral_arguments/argument_transcripts/12-96.pdf Transcript of Oral Argument from Feb 27, 2013]</ref> Media coverage of the Justices' comments during oral arguments portrayed the Court as appearing likely to hold Section 5 or Section 4(b) unconstitutional.<ref name=\"oral-1\">{{cite news|last=Reilly|first=Ryan J.|title=Voting Rights Act Supreme Court Case: Scalia Condemns The 'Perpetuation Of Racial Entitlement'|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/02/27/voting-rights-act-supreme-court_n_2768942.html|accessdate=13 July 2013|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=27 Feb 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"oral-2\">{{cite news|last=Lengell|first=Sean|title=Scalia \u2018racial\u2019 comment on voting rights law draws fire|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/feb/28/scalia-racial-comment-draws-fire|accessdate=13 July 2013|newspaper=The Washington Times|date=Feb 28, 2013}}</ref> Justice [[Antonin Scalia]] drew criticism from civil rights leaders, after expressing his belief during oral arguments that Congress reauthorized Section 5, not because the legislation was necessary, but because it constituted a \"racial entitlement\" that Congress was unlikely to end.<ref name=\"oral-1\" /><ref name=\"oral-2\" /><ref name=\"oral-3\">{{cite news|last=Goodwin|first=Liz|title=Civil rights leaders outraged over Scalia\u2019s \u2018racial entitlement\u2019 argument|url=https://news.yahoo.com/blogs/ticket/civil-rights-leaders-outraged-over-scalia-racial-entitlement-172338534--election.html|accessdate=13 July 2013|newspaper=Yahoo! News|date=28 Feb 2013}}</ref>\n\nA coalition of [https://ag.ny.gov/sites/default/files/press-releases/2011/ShelbyAmicusBrief.pdf 4 states provided an amicus brief] to the Supreme Court expressing support for Section 5 and noting that the preclearance provision did not impose a burden on them. That coalition was [https://ag.ny.gov/press-release/ag-schneiderman-takes-legal-action-protect-voting-rights-act-against-constitutional led by New York] and included Mississippi, North Carolina and California.\n\n== Opinion of the Supreme Court ==\nThe Supreme Court struck down Section 4(b) as unconstitutional in its June 25, 2013 ruling.<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\" /><ref name=\"THP20130625\">{{cite news|title=Voting Rights Act Section 4 Struck Down By Supreme Court|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/25/voting-rights-act-supreme-court_n_3429810.html|accessdate=7 July 2013|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=25 June 2013|author=Ryan J. Reilly, Mike Sacks and Sabrina Siddiqu}}</ref> The [[majority opinion]] was delivered by Chief Justice [[John Roberts]] joined by Justices [[Antonin Scalia]], [[Anthony Kennedy]], [[Clarence Thomas]], and [[Samuel Alito]].<ref name=\"NBC20130625\" /><ref name=\"rolls back\">{{cite news| url=http://swampland.time.com/2013/06/25/high-court-rolls-back-the-voting-rights-act-of-1965/ |title=High Court Rolls Back the Voting Rights Act of 1965 | work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date=2013-06-25 | accessdate=2013-06-25 | author=Von Drehle, David|authorlink=David Von Drehle}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Barnes|first=Robert|title=Supreme Court stops use of key part of Voting Rights Act|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/supreme-court-stops-use-of-key-part-of-voting-rights-act/2013/06/25/26888528-dda5-11e2-b197-f248b21f94c4_story.html|accessdate=29 June 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=25 June 2013}}</ref> The Court held that Section 4(b) exceeded Congress's power to enforce the Fourteenth and Fifteenth Amendments, reasoning that the coverage formula conflicts with the constitutional principles of [[Federalism in the United States|federalism]] and \"equal sovereignty of the states\" because the disparate treatment of the states is \"based on 40 year-old facts having no logical relationship to the present day\" and thus is not responsive to current needs.<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\" /><ref name=\"oyez\" /> The Court expressed that Congress cannot subject a state to preclearance based simply on past discrimination. It noted that since the coverage formula was last modified in 1975, the country \"has changed, and while any racial discrimination in voting is too much, Congress must ensure that the legislation it passes to remedy that problem speaks to current conditions\".<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\" /><ref name=\"SCOTUSBlogShapiro\">{{cite web|last=Shapiro|first=Ilya|title=Supreme Court recognizes Jim Crow's demise, restores constitutional order|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/?p=165978|publisher=SCOTUSblog|accessdate=5 July 2013|date=25 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|last=Cohen|first=Andrew|title=On Voting Rights, a Decision as Lamentable as Plessy or Dred Scott|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/national/archive/2013/06/on-voting-rights-a-decision-as-lamentable-as-plessy-or-dred-scott/276455/|accessdate=7 July 2013|work=The Atlantic|date=25 June 2013}}</ref> The Court declared that the Fifteenth Amendment \"commands that the right to vote shall not be denied or abridged on account of race or color, and it gives Congress the power to enforce that command. The Amendment is not designed to punish for the past; its purpose is to ensure a better future.\"<ref name=\"NYT20130625\" />\n\nRoberts wrote that the Act was immensely successful \"at redressing racial discrimination and integrating the voting process\u201d and noted that the U.S. has made great progress thanks to the Act.<ref name=\"NBC20130625\" /> But he added: \u201cIf Congress had started from scratch in 2006, it plainly could not have enacted the present coverage formula.\u201d<ref name=\"NBC20130625\">{{cite news|title=Supreme Court strikes down part of Voting Rights Act|url=http://nbcpolitics.nbcnews.com/_news/2013/06/25/19132385-supreme-court-strikes-down-part-of-voting-rights-act?lite|accessdate=27 August 2013|newspaper=NBCNews|date=25 June 2013|author=Pete Williams and Erin McClam}}</ref> According to the Court, \"Regardless of how to look at the record no one can fairly say that it shows anything approaching the 'pervasive,' 'flagrant,' 'widespread,' and 'rampant' discrimination that faced Congress in 1965, and that clearly distinguished the covered jurisdictions from the rest of the nation.\"<ref name=\"NYT20130625\">{{cite news|title=Between the Lines of the Voting Rights Act Opinion|author=Schwartz, John|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/06/25/us/annotated-supreme-court-decision-on-voting-rights-act.html?ref=us&_r=0|newspaper=The New York Times|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=25 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2013/06/opinion-recap-voting-law-in-deep-peril/|title=Open recap: Voting law in deep peril|last=Lyle|first=Denniston|date=June 25, 2013|publisher=[[SCOTUSblog]]|accessdate=June 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Court did not subject Section 4(b) to the \"[[Congressional power of enforcement|congruence and proportionality]]\" standard of review or address whether that standard is the appropriate measure to use when determining the constitutionality of legislation passed pursuant to Section 2 of the Fifteenth Amendment.<ref name=\"Hasen-congruence\">{{cite news|last=Hasen|first=Richard|title=The curious disappearance of Boerne and the future jurisprudence of voting rights and race|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/?p=165958|accessdate=5 August 2013|newspaper=SCOTUSblog|date=25 June 2013}}</ref> The Court also noted the federalism concerns raised by the Section 5 preclearance requirement, but it did not reach the issue of whether Section 5 remains constitutional. However, because the Section 5 preclearance requirement applies only to jurisdictions covered by the Section 4(b) coverage formula, the decision rendered Section 5 inoperable unless Congress enacts a new coverage formula.<ref name=\"plain-english\" /><ref name=\"THP20130625\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|title=The Formula Behind the Voting Rights Act|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/06/23/us/voting-rights-act-map.html|accessdate=8 July 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=22 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nJustice Thomas wrote a [[concurring opinion]] expressing his view that Section 5 is also unconstitutional for the same reasons the Court held Section 4(b) unconstitutional.<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\" /><ref name=\"NYT20130626\">{{cite news|title=Supreme Court Invalidates Key Part of Voting Rights Act|author=Liptak, Adam|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/26/us/supreme-court-ruling.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=26 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nJustice [[Ruth Bader Ginsburg]] wrote a [[dissenting opinion]] that was joined by Justices [[Stephen Breyer]], [[Sonia Sotomayor]], and [[Elana Kagan|Elena Kagan]]. The dissent would have held that Congress had sufficient evidence before it to determine that the coverage formula remained responsive to current needs. The dissent acknowledged that discrimination in voting has decreased in the covered jurisdictions since the Voting Rights Act's enactment, but it attributed much of that decrease to the Act itself, noting that \"[t]hrowing out preclearance when it has worked and is continuing to work to stop discriminatory changes is like throwing away your umbrella in a rainstorm because you are not getting wet.\"<ref name=\"scotus-opinion\" /><ref name=\"oyez\" /><ref name=\"NYT20130625\"/>\n\n==Reaction==\nThe controversial Supreme Court opinion prompted heavy media coverage of reactions from political leaders, activists, and the legal community. President [[Barack Obama]] expressed deep disappointment with the decision and called on Congress \"to pass legislation to ensure every American has equal access to the polls\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Voting Rights Act Section 4 Struck Down By Supreme Court |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/25/obama-voting-rights-act_n_3497124.html|accessdate=5 July 2013 |newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=25 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Jackson|first=David|title=Obama 'disappointed' in court's voting rights decision |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/theoval/2013/06/25/obama-supreme-court-voting-rights-act/2455939|accessdate=5 July 2013|newspaper=USA Today|date=25 June 2013}}</ref> Attorney General [[Eric Holder]] also expressed disappointment with the decision, and he pledged that the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] \"will not hesitate to take swift enforcement action\u2014using every legal tool that remains available to us\u2014against any jurisdiction that seeks to take advantage of the Supreme Court's ruling by hindering eligible citizens' full and free exercise of the franchise\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Reilly |first=Ryan |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/25/eric-holder-voting-rights-act_n_3496909.html|title=Eric Holder Warns Voting Rights Act Decision Could 'Negatively Affect Millions Of Americans'|accessdate=5 July 2013|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=25 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Holder: 'Deeply disappointed' in ruling |url=http://www.cnn.com/video/data/2.0/video/politics/2013/06/25/sot-atw-scotus-voting-rights-holder.cnn.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=5 July 2013|date=25 June 2013}}</ref> On July 25, 2013, Holder announced that the Department of Justice would ask a federal court to subject the formerly covered state of [[Texas]] to preclearance under the \"bail in\" provision contained in Section 3 of the Voting Rights Act, which was unaffected by the Court's decision.<ref>{{cite news |last=Millhiser|first=Ian|title=Justice Department Will Ask Court To Reinstate Voting Rights Act In Texas |url=http://thinkprogress.org/justice/2013/07/25/2354501/breaking-justice-department-will-ask-court-to-reinstate-voting-rights-act-in-texas/?mobile=nc|accessdate=27 July 2013|date=27 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Coyle|first=Marcia|title=DOJ Messes With Texas Over VRA|url=http://www.law.com/jsp/nlj/PubArticleNLJ.jsp?id=1202612526515|accessdate=27 July 2013|newspaper=The National Law Journal|date=25 July 2013|author2=Rugger, Todd}}</ref>\n\nWhen asked whether a polarized Congress could agree on a new coverage formula, Speaker [[John Boehner]] acknowledged the importance of the role of the Voting Rights Act over the previous 40 years and said that he was still reviewing the decision and trying to determine the next steps. Then [[Party leaders of the United States House of Representatives#Job description|House Majority Leader]] [[Eric Cantor]] expressed his hope that Congress would \"put politics aside\" and determine how to ensure that voting rights remain protected.<ref name=congressional-republicans>{{cite news|last=McAuliff|first=Michael|title=John Boehner, Republicans Show No Signs Of Fixing Voting Rights Act |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/26/john-boehner-voting-rights_n_3503714.html|accessdate=5 July 2013 |newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=26 June 2013}}</ref> Representative [[John Lewis (Georgia politician)|John Lewis]], a leader in the civil rights movement who was present when President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] signed the Voting Rights Act into law, said that the decision disregarded the country's history of voting discrimination and that he fears the decision will allow local election officials \"to go back to another period\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Zeleny|first=Jeff|title=John Lewis: Court\u2019s Decision Puts 'Dagger in Heart of Voting Rights Act' |url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2013/06/courts-decision-puts-dagger-in-heart-of-voting-rights-act/|accessdate=5 July 2013|publisher=ABC News|date=25 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=outrage-overdue>{{cite news |last=Mears|first=Bill|title='Outrageous' or overdue?: Court strikes down part of historic voting rights law |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/06/25/politics/scotus-voting-rights|publisher=CNN|accessdate=5 July 2013|author2=Botelho, Greg|date=26 June 2013}}</ref> Representative [[Bob Goodlatte]], Chair of the [[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|House Judiciary Committee]], said that the committee will review new voting data but that he is unsure whether the committee will take any specific action in response to the decision.<ref>{{cite news|last=Killough|first=Ashley|title=Goodlatte unsure if Congress will take up Voting Rights Act|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2013/06/30/goodlatte-unsure-if-congress-will-take-up-voting-rights-act |accessdate=11 July 2013|publisher=CNN|date=30 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=senate-hearings>{{cite news|last=Whitaker|first=Morgan|title=Senate committee moving forward on Voting Rights Act|url=http://tv.msnbc.com/2013/07/10/senate-committee-moving-forward-on-voting-rights-act/|accessdate=11 July 2013|publisher=MSNBC|date=10 July 2013}}</ref> On July 18, 2013, the [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on the Constitution and Civil Justice|House Judiciary Subcommittee on the Constitution and Civil Justice]] held a hearing to discuss how the House should respond to the ruling.<ref>{{cite news|title=Congress divided on voting rights fix |url=http://www.greenvilleonline.com/article/20130719/NEWS/307190007/Congress-divided-voting-rights-fix |accessdate=19 July 2013|newspaper=GreenvilleOnline.com|date=18 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nSenate Majority Leader [[Harry Reid]] said that [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] were concerned with the ruling in light of \"[[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] doing everything they could to suppress voting\" in the 2012 elections, and he stated that the Senate will act to address the decision.<ref>{{cite news |last=Van Dongen|first=Rachel|title=Harry Reid: Senate 'will act' on Voting Rights Act |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/06/voting-rights-act-harry-reid-senate-93344.html|accessdate=5 July 2013 |newspaper=Politico|date=25 June 2013|author2=Everett, Burgess}}</ref> Senator [[Bob Corker]], however, said that he \"cannot imagine\" Congress ever agreeing on the terms of a new coverage formula.<ref name=congressional-republicans /><ref>{{cite news|last=Bendery|first=Jennifer|title=Bob Corker On Voting Rights Act: 'Cannot Imagine' Congress Restoring It |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/25/bob-corker-voting-rights-act_n_3499352.html|accessdate=5 July 2013 |newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=25 July 2013}}</ref> The [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Senate Judiciary Committee]] began to hold hearings on July 17, 2013 to discuss how to respond to the decision.<ref name=senate-hearings /><ref>{{cite news|last=Melber|first=Ari|title=Senate tackles Voting Rights Act |url=http://tv.msnbc.com/2013/07/17/senate-tackles-voting-rights-act/|accessdate=18 July 2013 |publisher=MSNBC|date=17 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt the state level, Texas and [[Mississippi]] officials pledged within hours of the decision to enforce voter ID laws that had not been precleared by the Attorney General.<ref>{{cite news|last=Applewhite|first=Scott|title=For Republicans, no easy answers on Voting Rights Act |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-250_162-57592414/for-republicans-no-easy-answers-on-voting-rights-act |accessdate=5 July 2013|publisher=CBS News|date=5 July 2013}}</ref> [[Florida]] Secretary of State Ken Detzner said it made no sense for five Florida counties to be subjected to preclearance based on decades-old voting rights data and that the decision will save the state money.<ref>{{cite news|last=Klas|first=Mary Ellen|title=Court blocks application of Voting Rights Act in Florida, unless Congress updates rules |url=http://miamiherald.typepad.com/nakedpolitics/2013/06/court-blocks-application-of-voting-rights-act-in-florida-unless-congress-updates-rules.html |accessdate=5 July 2013|newspaper=Miami Herald|date=25 June 2013}}</ref> [[New York (state)|New York]] Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] found the decision deeply troubling and called upon Congress to pass a new coverage formula.<ref>{{cite news |last=Katz|first=Celeste|title=SCOTUS And The Voting Rights Act, Part 5: Ruling 'Deeply Troubling', Gov. Cuomo Says|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/2013/06/scotus-and-the-voting-rights-act-part-5-ruling-deeply-troubling-gov-cuomo-says |accessdate=5 July 2013|newspaper= New York Daily News|date=25 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nIlya Shapiro of the [[Cato Institute]] said that the Supreme Court's decision \"restore[d] the constitutional order, the status quo ante the temporary Sections 4/5, because there is no longer systemic racial disenfranchisement, or at the very least in the covered jurisdictions\".<ref name=\"SCOTUSBlogShapiro\" /> In contrast, Jon Greenbaum, chief counsel of the [[Lawyers' Committee for Civil Rights Under Law]], said that because of the decision, \"[m]inority voters in places with a record of discrimination are now at greater risk of being disenfranchised than they have been in decades\" and that their only recourse will be to pursue expensive litigation.<ref>{{cite news|last=De Vogue|first=Ariane|title=Supreme Court Strikes Down Key Part of Voting Rights Act|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/supreme-court-strikes-portion-voting-rights-act/story?id=19459258|accessdate=5 July 2013|publisher=ABC News|date=25 June 2013}}</ref> [[Penda Hair]], co-director of national racial justice organization [[Advancement Project]], spoke along similar lines, saying, \"The Supreme Court's ruling rolls back legislation that courageous Americans fought so hard for, even giving their lives in many cases, to ensure that all citizens can participate in our democracy. Today's decision threatens the promise of equal access to the ballot \u2013 especially when the majority of voters of color who voted last year, 65.8 percent, live in states covered by the Section 4 formula.\"<ref>[http://www.advancementproject.org/news/entry/scotus-removes-critical-protection-for-voters-of-color \"SCOTUS Removes Critical Protection for Voters of Color\"], ''Advancement Project'', June 25, 2013</ref>\n\nAn investigation by [[ProPublica]] in October 2017 revealed that Chief Justice John Roberts used erroneous data in the ruling.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/supreme-court-errors-are-not-hard-to-find|title=It's a Fact: Supreme Court Errors Aren't Hard to Find |date=2017-10-17|website=ProPublica|language=en-us|first=Ryan |last=Gabrielson|accessdate=2017-10-17}}</ref> Roberts claimed that the registration gap between blacks and whites had shrunk dramatically in southern states since the Civil Rights Act of 1965, thus calling into question why six southern states were subject to stringent oversight.<ref name=\":3\" /> Roberts included Hispanics into his numbers for whites, including even those who could not register to vote because they were not U.S. citizens, thereby making the newly \"white\" registration rate lower than what it would have been.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Impact==\nSince the ruling, several states once covered under preclearance have passed laws that removed provisions such as online voting registration, early voting, \"Souls to the Polls\" Sunday voting, same-day registration, and pre-registration for teens about to turn 18. The ruling has also resulted in some states implementing voter identification laws and becoming more aggressive in expunging allegedly ineligible voters from registration rolls.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fuller|first1=Jaime|title=How has voting changed since Shelby County v. Holder?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2014/07/07/how-has-voting-changed-since-shelby-county-v-holder/|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=July 7, 2014}}</ref> States that have changed their voting policies post-Shelby include both jurisdictions that were previously required to undergo federal preclearance, as well as some that were not covered, including Alabama, Arizona, Arkansas, North Carolina, Ohio, Wisconsin and Texas. According to the Brennan Center for Justice, the states most likely to enact voting restrictions were states with the highest African-American turnout in the 2008 election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brennancenter.org/analysis/election-2016-restrictive-voting-laws-numbers|title=Election 2016: Restrictive Voting Laws by the Numbers |publisher=Brennan Center for Justice |language=en|accessdate=2018-12-22}}</ref>\n\nThree years after the ruling, 868 polling places had been closed down.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomsbury.com/us/one-person-no-vote-9781635571387/|title=One Person, No Vote|last=Anderson|first=Carol|date=2018|website=www.bloomsbury.com|accessdate=2018-12-22|quote=Because of ''Shelby County v. Holder'', by 2016, there were 868 fewer precincts in Section 5 jurisdictions.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2016/11/4/13501120/vote-polling-places-election-2016|title=Southern states have closed down at least 868 polling places for the 2016 election|last=Lopez|first=German|date=2016-11-04|website=Vox|accessdate=2018-12-22}}</ref> Five years after the ruling, nearly a thousand polling places had been closed in the country, with many of the closed polling places in predominantly African-American counties. Research shows that the changing of voter locations and reduction in voting locations can reduce voter turnout.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.pewtrusts.org/research-and-analysis/blogs/stateline/2018/09/04/polling-places-remain-a-target-ahead-of-november-elections|title=Polling Place Politics|website=www.pewtrusts.org|accessdate=2018-09-05}}</ref> A 2018 report by the [[United States Commission on Civil Rights|U.S. Commission on Civil Rights]] (a bipartisan, independent commission of the United States federal government) found that there had been a growth in discriminatory laws making it harder for minorities to vote. The commission found that at least 23 states enacted restrictive voter laws, such as closures of polling places, cuts to early voting, purges of voter rolls and imposition of strict voter ID laws. The commission chair said people \"continue to suffer significant, and profoundly unequal, limitations on their ability to vote&nbsp;... That stark reality denigrates our democracy and diminishes our ideals. This level of ongoing discrimination confirms what was true before 1965, when the Voting Rights Act became law, and has remained true since 1965: Americans need strong and effective federal protections to guarantee that ours is a real democracy.\"<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" />\n\nA 2017 study in the ''[[American Journal of Political Science]]'' by Boston University political scientist Sophie Schuit\u00a0and Harvard University political scientist Jon C. Rogowski found that the preclearance requirement in the Voting Rights Act led to greater representation of Black interests, and this effect persisted long after the passage of the Voting Rights Act. The authors of the study note that this finding is contrary to the \"majority's opinion in ''Shelby County v. Holder'' that 'things have changed' and that the issues addressed by the VRA are 'decades\u2010old problems'. To the contrary, preclearance under the VRA appeared to substantially increase Black representation in the contemporary era.\"<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite journal|last=Schuit|first=Sophie|last2=Rogowski|first2=Jon C.|date=2017|title=Race, Representation, and the Voting Rights Act|journal=American Journal of Political Science|language=en|volume=61|issue=3|pages=513\u2013526|doi=10.1111/ajps.12284|issn=1540-5907}}</ref>\n\nA 2019 study in the ''American Economic Journal'' found that preclearance substantially increased turnout among minorities, even as far as to 2012 (the year prior to the Supreme Court ruling ending preclearance).<ref name=\":9\" /> The study estimates that preclearance led to an increase in minority turnout of 17 percentage points.<ref name=\":9\" /> \n\nVirtually all restrictions on voting subsequent to the ruling were by Republicans.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/03/us/politics/voting-suppression-elections.html|title='They Don't Really Want Us to Vote': How Republicans Made it Harder| first1=Danny |last1=Hakim |first2=Michael |last2=Wines|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=3 November 2018|accessdate=2018-11-04|language=en}}</ref> Numerous strict voter ID laws have been passed in states that required preclearance under the Civil Rights Act. Such laws were passed for the stated reason of preventing vote fraud; however, there is no evidence of widespread voter fraud, and critics say these laws are intended to make it harder for minorities to vote.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://bostonreview.net/politics/ariel-white-voter-id-laws|title=Voter Discrimination Starts Well Before Election Day|last=White|first=Ariel|date=2016-10-31|website=Boston Review|language=en|accessdate=2018-12-22}}</ref> According to MIT political scientist Ariel White, there is evidence that voter ID laws have a disparate impact on minority voting whereas there is little evidence that voter-ID laws prevent voter fraud.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n===Alabama===\nAfter ''Shelby'', Alabama Republicans drew a new legislative apportionment map of the state that some{{who|date=March 2019}} contend is illegal. Democrats said that the new map packs African-American voters into too few voting districts and is an effort to hamper the power of the largely Democratic voting base.<ref name=Hananel_Sam>{{cite news|last1=Hananel|first1=Sam|title=Supreme Court To Hear Alabama Redistricting Challenge|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/06/02/supreme-court-alabama-redistricting_n_5431345.html|work=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=2 July 2015|date=June 6, 2014|quote=The U.S. Supreme Court cases are ''Alabama Legislative Black Caucus v. State of Alabama'', 13-895, and ''Alabama Democratic Conference v. Alabama'', 13-1138.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the Supreme Court said it would hear appeals from the Alabama Legislative Black Caucus regarding the redistricting.<ref name=Hananel_Sam />\n\n===Arizona===\nIn an opinion issued by Arizona's attorney general in 2013, Arizona residents who registered to vote using forms provided by the federal government must also provide documentation proving their citizenship, or their registration will be labeled invalid. Attorney General Tom Horne said those who registered using federal registration could vote in federal elections, but not state and local elections without showing proof of citizenship. The attorney general also held that these same registrants will not be able to sign petitions for candidates or ballot initiatives.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilson|first1=Reid|title=Arizona law may restrict voting in local elections |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/govbeat/wp/2013/10/09/arizona-law-may-restrict-voting-in-local-elections/|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=October 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===North Carolina===\nShortly after the Shelby ruling, North Carolina [[Pat McCrory|Gov. Pat McCrory]] signed into law H.B. 589, which terminated valid out-of-precinct voting, same-day registration during the early voting period, and pre-registration for teenagers about to turn 18, while also enacting a voter ID law. Opponents criticized this law as adversely affecting minority voters.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Baggett|first1=Leela|title=North Carolina H.B. 589: Putting Up Barriers For Voters Who Move |url=http://www.projectvote.org/blog/2013/08/north-carolinas-h-b-589-putting-up-barriers-for-voters-who-move/|work=Project Vote Blog|accessdate=July 2, 2015|date=August 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe law was challenged, on behalf of the North Carolina State Conference of the NAACP, by a lawsuit filed by Advancement Project, pro bono counsel [[Kirkland & Ellis]], and North Carolina attorneys Adam Stein and Irv Joyner. The suit alleged that the law violates Section 2 of the Voting Rights Act, as well as the 14th and 15th Amendments of the U.S. Constitution.<ref>{{cite web|title=North Carolina State Conference of the NAACP v. McCrory |url=http://www.advancementproject.org/pages/north-carolina-vpp|publisher=Advancement Project|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn July 29, 2016, a three-judge panel of the [[Fourth Circuit Court of Appeals]] reversed a trial court decision in a number of consolidated actions, finding that the new voting provisions targeted African Americans \"with almost surgical precision\" and that the legislators had acted with \"discriminatory intent\" in enacting strict election rules; the Court struck down the law's photo ID requirement and changes to early voting, preregistration, same-day registration and out-of-district voting.<ref>{{cite news |author=Ann E. Marimow |title=Appeals court strikes down North Carolina's voter-ID law |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/appeals-court-strikes-down-north-carolinas-voter-id-law/2016/07/29/810b5844-4f72-11e6-aa14-e0c1087f7583_story.html |work=Washington Post |date=July 29, 2016 |accessdate=2016-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/north-carolina-voter-id_us_579b8862e4b08a8e8b5de534|title=North Carolina Voter ID Law Targeted African-Americans, Appeals Court Rules|author1=Julia Harte|author2=Andy Sullivan|date=July 29, 2016|newspaper=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n\n===North Dakota===\nAs of October 10, 2018, an act of North Dakota was upheld by the United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit<ref name=North_Dakota_CourtRuling2018>https://ecf.ca8.uscourts.gov/opndir/18/09/181725P.pdf</ref> which requires individuals who vote to have a voter ID which has their name, street address, and date of birth. At the time the state's Native reservations did not generally have street addresses, only post boxes for residents; there was concern that this provision would disproportionately affect Native voting,<ref>https://www.wbur.org/hereandnow/2018/10/23/north-dakota-voter-id-law-native-americans</ref> and speculation that it was drafted with that as a primary goal.<ref>https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/native-americans-fighting-back-against-north-dakota-voter-id-law-n926326</ref>\n\nDissenters Justices Ginsburg and Kagan said, \"The risk of [[voter confusion]] appears severe here because the injunction against requiring residential-address identification was in force during the primary election and because the Secretary of State\u2019s website announced for months the ID requirements as they existed under that injunction.\"{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Ohio===\nIn February 2014, the Ohio House approved a bill that eliminated the so-called \"Golden Week\" during which Ohio voters could register and vote on the same day. The bill also cut six days from Ohio's early voting period. In a separate bill, the House made it easier for registrars to reject absentee ballots for missing information. This bill ends a program that mailed absentee ballots to all registered voters. Under the new law, Ohio's secretary of state would have to get lawmaker approval to mail these absentee ballots.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Higgs |first1=Robert |title=Kasich signs voting bills that end Golden Week and limit distribution of absentee ballots |url=http://www.cleveland.com/open/index.ssf/2014/02/kasich_signs_voting_bills_that.html|accessdate=2 July 2015 |work=www.cleveland.com|publisher=Northeast Ohio Media Group Columbus|date=February 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Texas===\nWhile its voter ID law was passed in 2011, Texas did not enact the law until 2013 after the ''Shelby'' ruling, when the state was no longer subject to federal preclearance for changes to its voting laws. Under the law, Texas voters must show a photo ID to vote. While there are some exemptions, such as for voters with disabilities, most are required to produce a Texas driver's license or state ID card. Other forms of acceptable ID include concealed handgun licenses, military ID, U.S. citizenship papers with photo and a U.S. passport.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Langford|first1=Terri|title=Criminal Appeals Court Judge Files Suit Over Voter ID |url=http://www.texastribune.org/2014/10/02/criminal-appeals-court-judge-files-voter-id-lawsui/|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=The Texas Tribune|date=October 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIf the voter does not possess one of the forms of acceptable photo ID and cannot reasonably obtain one, the voter may present one of the following, after which he or she must execute a Reasonable Impediment Declaration:<ref>http://www.sos.state.tx.us/elections/forms/pol-sub/reasonable-impediment-declaration.pdf</ref> a copy or original of a government document that shows the voter's name and an address, including the voter's voter registration certificate; a current utility bill; a bank statement; a government check; a paycheck; or (a) a certified domestic (from a U.S. state or territory) birth certificate or (b) a document confirming birth admissible in a court of law which establishes the voter's identity (which may include a foreign birth document).<ref>http://www.votetexas.gov/register-to-vote/need-id.html|Required Identification for Voting in Person</ref>\n\nCritics of the law{{who?|date=September 2018}} charge that it is unconstitutional. They also say that it will bar legitimate voters from voting and discourage citizens. Examples of problems under the new law involved public figures: Texas judge, Sandra Watts, was unable to vote because the name on her photo ID did not match the name on the voter rolls. Also, State Senator Wendy Davis and then-Attorney General Greg Abbott were delayed in voting under the new law. They were all able to vote after signing affidavits attesting that they were who they claimed to be.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lyman|first1=Rick|title=Texas' Stringent Voter ID Law Makes a Dent at Polls |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/07/us/politics/texas-stringent-voter-id-law-makes-a-dent-at-polls.html|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=The New York Times|date=November 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Wisconsin===\nIn 2014, the American Civil Liberties Union and the Advancement Project filed a petition asking the Supreme Court to block Wisconsin's voter ID law, charging the measure would disproportionately affect voters of color.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilson|first1=Reid|title=Voting rights advocates want Supreme Court to block Wisconsin voter ID law|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/govbeat/wp/2014/10/02/voting-rights-advocates-want-supreme-court-to-block-wisconsin-voter-id-law/|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=October 2, 2014}}</ref> Challenging the law under Section 2 of the Voting Rights Act and the U.S. Constitution, Advancement Project litigated on behalf of the League of United Latin American Citizens of Wisconsin, Cross Lutheran Church, Wisconsin League of Young Voters Education Fund, and the Milwaukee Area Labor Council of the AFL-CIO.<ref name=\"Advancement Project20141009\">{{cite web|last1=Gordy|first1=Cynthia|title=Wisconsin Voter ID Law Halted, as Supreme Court Blocks Appeals Court Order|url=http://www.advancementproject.org/news/entry/wisconsin-voter-id-law-halted-as-supreme-court-blocks-appeals-court-order|publisher=Advancement Project|accessdate=2 July 2015|date=October 9, 2014}}</ref> Advancement Project claimed that Wisconsin's voter ID law, enacted in 2012, is \"part of a broader attack on the right to vote\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Farmer|first1=Jennifer|title=Advocates To Challenge Wisconsin's Anti-Voting Law In Federal Court|url=http://www.advancementproject.org/news/entry/advocates-to-challenge-wisconsins-anti-voting-law-in-federal-court|publisher=Advancement Project|accessdate=2 July 2015|date=October 30, 2014}}</ref> On October 9, 2014, the U.S. Supreme Court issued an emergency stay in this case, blocking a Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals order to implement Wisconsin\u2019s voter ID law and enabling registration under previous rules for the fall of 2014 elections. It has yet to rule on the provisions of Wisconsin's law.<ref name=\"Advancement Project20141009\" />\n\n== Legislative responses ==\nOn January 16, 2014, a bipartisan group of members of Congress, consisting of Representatives [[Jim Sensenbrenner]] and [[John Conyers]] and Senator [[Patrick Leahy]], introduced H.R.3899/S.R.1945,<ref name=\"20140428VRAFORTODAY\">{{cite web|last1=Lewis|first1=Tyler|title=Bill Summary: Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2014|url=http://vrafortoday.org/?attachment_id=252|publisher=VRA for Today|accessdate=4 July 2015|date=April 28, 2014|quote=See also http://vrafortoday.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/2014-04-07-VRAA-Bill-Summary_c4.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150707095901/http://vrafortoday.org/?attachment_id=252|archivedate=7 July 2015}}</ref> entitled the Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2014. The bill was introduced to strengthen the Voting Rights Act of 1965 (VRA) and vital protections of it following the 2013 Supreme Court's decision in ''Shelby County v. Holder''.<ref name=\"TheNation20150116\" /> The proposed Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2014 consists of five components:<ref name=\"20140428VRAFORTODAY\" /><ref name=\"TheNation20150116\">{{cite news |last1=Berman |first1=Ari |title=Members of Congress Introduce a New Fix for the Voting Rights Act |url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/177962/members-congress-introduce-new-fix-voting-rights-act#|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=[[The Nation]]|date=January 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n# Based on empirical conditions and current data there is a new coverage formula for Section 4 based on a rolling calendar, updated with a current fifteen-year time period to exempt states who are no longer discriminating or add new ones who are. The last part is designed to create a deterrent against future voting rights violations. Under the new formula states with five violations of federal law to their voting changes over the past fifteen years will have to submit future election changes for federal approval. Local jurisdictions would be covered if they commit three or more violations or have one violation and \"persistent, extremely low minority turnout\" over the past fifteen years. While Voter ID laws can still be blocked by the Department of Justice in the new states covered under Section 4, objections to voter ID laws by the department will not count as a new violation.\n# Section 3 of the bill makes it possible that a court may order jurisdictions not covered by Section 4 to have future changes to its election laws preapproved by the federal government after plaintiffs file a corresponding application with the court. Plaintiffs have to show evidence of intentional voting discrimination to enable such a bail-in. Any violation of the VRA or of federal voting rights law\u2014whether intentional or not\u2014can be under the new section 3 proposal grounds for a bail-in, but court objections to voter ID laws that are not found to be intentionally discriminatory cannot be used as grounds for \"bail-in\" under Section 3.\n# Jurisdictions in all U.S. states have to provide notice in the local media and online of any election procedures related to redistricting, changes within 180 days of a federal election and the moving of a polling place. Citizens can thus easier identify potentially harmful voting changes in states not subject to Sections 4 and 5 of the VRA.\n# Plaintiffs seeking a preliminary injunction against a potentially discriminatory voting law must only show that the hardship to them outweighs the hardship to the state if a law is blocked in court pending a full trial.\n# Affirming the attorney general's authority to send federal observers in states subject to Section 4 to monitor elections in these states the proposal expands the attorney general's authority to send observers to jurisdictions with a history of discriminating against language minority groups.\n\nAs of June 2014 the proposed Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2014 was in limbo because there is no widespread support to amend the Voting Rights Act as it was by its re-authorization in 2006 by Congress.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fuller|first1=Jaime|title=Republicans used to unanimously back the Voting Rights Act. Not any more |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2014/06/26/republicans-used-to-unanimously-back-voting-rights-act-not-any-more/ |accessdate=2 July 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=June 26, 2014}}</ref> Both the House and Senate versions of the bill ultimately died in their respective Judiciary Committees.<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3899 (113th): Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2014|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr3899|publisher=[[GovTrack]]|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=S. 1945 (113th): Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2014| url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/s1945|publisher=[[GovTrack]]|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref> The House introduced the Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2015 the following year.<ref>{{cite web|title=All Bill Information (Except Text) for H.R. 885 \u2013 Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2015 |url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/885/all-info|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|accessdate=6 October 2015|date=2015-03-16}}</ref> It was referred to the House Judiciary Committee on the day it was introduced, but did not move past the committee stage.<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R. 885 (114th): Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2015|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr885|publisher=[[GovTrack]]|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref> The Voting Rights Advancement Act of 2015 (H.R. 2867), a similar measure to the Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2015, was introduced on June 24, 2015, but died with the end of the [[114th United States Congress]].<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R. 2867 (114th): Voting Rights Advancement Act of 2015|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr2867|website=[[GovTrack]]|publisher=[[GovTrack]]|accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> The most recent legislative attempt, the Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2017 (H.R. 3239), was introduced on July 13, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3239: Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2017|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/115/hr3239|website=[[GovTrack]]|accessdate=October 13, 2017}}</ref> and again referred to the House Judiciary Committee.<ref>{{cite web|title=All Information (Except Text) for H.R.3239 \u2013 Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2017|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-bill/3239/all-info|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|accessdate=13 October 2017|date=2017-08-03}}</ref>\n\nNew York Senator [[Kirsten Gillibrand]] proposed to make online voter registration universal. Under her proposal states with existing online access would expand their system beyond those with state-issued IDs to allow more young people, seniors, minorities and the poor access and update their own voter records online. To ensure security, online systems will verify voter's eligibility by checking each person's personal information, like date of birth, Social Security, and address.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Jill Castellano and Reuven Blau|title=Sen. Kirsten Gillibrand plans to introduce legislation to allow voters to register online |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/sen-kristen-gillibrand-expand-online-voter-registration-article-1.1839665 |accessdate=2 July 2015|work=The New York Daily News|date=June 22, 2014}}</ref> According to the [[Brennan Center for Justice]] at New York University Law School in 2014 several states (California, Colorado, Hawaii, Illinois, Louisiana, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Mississippi, Nebraska, Oklahoma, South Carolina, Utah) and Washington, D.C. passed laws improving voter access, while laws restricting voter access was only passed by a minority of states in 2014. Introduced and pending legislation to expand and improve access to registration and voting include as of December 2014 electronic transfer of voter registration information, online registration, portability i.e. the possibility to move a voter's registration with her when she moves to a new address within the same county or state, fail-safe protections, easier registration and voting for students, people with disabilities, military members and for voters who speak a language other than English as well as expansion of opportunities for voting registration and for early in-person voting.<ref>{{cite web|title=Voting Laws Roundup 2014 |url=http://www.brennancenter.org/analysis/voting-laws-roundup-2014|publisher=Brennan Center for Justice |accessdate=2 July 2015|date=December 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, congressional Democrats introduced the Voting Rights Advancement Act, which would restore the Voting Rights Act's preclearance provision, requiring certain jurisdictions to secure federal approval before enacting voting changes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/431693-democrats-introduce-bill-to-strengthen-voting-rights-act|title=Dems introduce bills to restore Voting Rights Act provision|last=Bowden|first=John|date=2019-02-26|website=The Hill|language=en|accessdate=2019-06-24}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{caselaw source\n | case = ''Shelby County v. Holder'', {{Ussc|570|529|2013|el=no}}\n | courtlistener =\n | googlescholar = https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=1305449212751290785\n | justia =\n | oyez =https://www.oyez.org/cases/2012/12-96\n | other_source1 = Supreme Court (slip opinion)\n | other_url1 =https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/12pdf/12-96_6k47.pdf\n}}\n\n[[Category:United States elections case law]]\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases]]\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases of the Roberts Court]]\n[[Category:2013 in United States case law]]\n[[Category:Shelby County, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Legal history of Alabama]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "ref name fixed; duplicate references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelby_County_v._Holder"}
{"title_page": "August Derleth bibliography", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia bibliography}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2020}}\nThis is a list of the writings of the American writer [[August Derleth]].\n\n==Novels==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n'''Sac Prairie Saga'''\n* ''Still is the Summer Night'' (1937)\n* ''Wind Over Wisconsin'' (1938)\n* ''Any Day Now'' (1938)\n* ''Restless is the River'' (1939)\n* ''Evening in Spring'' (1941)\n* ''Sweet Genevieve'' (1942)\n* ''Shadow of Night'' (1943)\n* ''The Shield of the Valiant'' (1945)\n* ''The House of Moonlight'' (1953)\n'''Other'''\n* ''Murder Stalks the Wakely Family'' (1934)\n* ''The Man on All Fours'' (1934)\n* ''Three Who Died'' (1935)\n* ''Sign of Fear'' (1935)\n* ''Sentence Deferred'' (1939)\n* ''The Narracong Riddle'' (1940)\n* ''Bright Journey'' (1940)\n* ''The Seven Who Waited'' (1943)\n* ''Mischief in the Lane'' (1944)\n* ''No Future for Luana'' (1945)\n* ''Oliver, The Wayward Owl'' (1945)\n* ''The Country of the Hawk'' (1952)\n* ''The Captive Island'' (1952)\n* ''Fell Purpose'' (1953)\n* ''Death by Design'' (1953)\n* ''Empire of Fur'' (1953)\n* ''Land of Gray Gold'' (1954)\n* ''Land of Sky Blue Waters'' (1955)\n* ''The House on the Mound'' (1958)\n* ''The Moon Tenders'' (1958) [The Mill Creek Irregulars #1]\n* ''Wilbur, The Trusting Whippoorwill'' (1959)\n* ''The Mill Creek Irregulars'' (1959) [The Mill Creek Irregulars #2]\n* ''The Pinkertons Ride Again'' (1960) [The Mill Creek Irregulars #3]\n* ''The Ghost of Blackhawk Island'' (1961) [The Mill Creek Irregulars #4]\n* ''Sweet Land of Michigan'' (1962)\n* ''The Tent Show Summer'' (1963) [The Mill Creek Irregulars #5]\n* ''The Irregulars Strike Again'' (1964) [The Mill Creek Irregulars #6]\n* ''The House by the River'' (1965) [The Mill Creek Irregulars #7]\n* ''The Watcher on the Heights'' (1966) [The Mill Creek Irregulars #8]\n* ''The Beast in Holger's Woods'' (1968)\n* ''The Prince Goes West'' (1968) [The Mill Creek Irregulars #9]\n* ''Three Straw Men'' (1970) [The Mill Creek Irregulars #10]\n}}\n\n==Sac Prairie Saga==\n* ''Place of Hawks'' (1935)\n* ''Country Growth'' (1940)\n* ''Wisconsin Earth: A Sac Prairie Sampler'' (1948)\n* ''Sac Prairie People'' (1948)\n* ''Wisconsin in Their Bones'' (1961)\n* ''Country Matters'' (1996)\n* ''Return to Sac Prairie'' (1996)\n* ''The Lost Sac Prairie Novels'' (2000), including ''The Odyssey of Janna Meade'' (first published in the ''[[Star Weekly]]'' magazine December 3, 1949); ''The Wind in the Cedars'' (also as ''Happiness Shall Not Escape'') (first published in Redbook Magazine, January 1946), ''Lamplight for the Dark'' (first published in Redbook Magazine January 1941); ''Shane's Girls'' (also as ''Happiness is a Gift'') (first published in Redbook Magazine 1948)\n\n==Solar Pons==\n* ''[[In Re: Sherlock Holmes|\"In Re: Sherlock Holmes\" \u2013 The Adventures of Solar Pons]]'' (UK: ''The Adventures of Solar Pons'') (1945)\n* ''[[The Memoirs of Solar Pons]]'' (1951)\n* ''[[Three Problems for Solar Pons]]'' (1952)\n* ''[[The Return of Solar Pons]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[The Reminiscences of Solar Pons]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[Mr. Fairlie's Final Journey]]'' (1968)\n* ''[[The Casebook of Solar Pons]]'' (1965)\n* ''[[A Praed Street Dossier]]'' (1968)\n* ''[[The Chronicles of Solar Pons]]'' (1973)\n* ''[[The Solar Pons Omnibus]]'' (1982)\n* ''[[The Final Adventures of Solar Pons]]'' (1998)\n\n''' Horror & Cthulhu Mythos'''\n* ''[[Someone in the Dark]]'' (1941)\n* ''[[Something Near]]'' (1945)\n* ''[[Not Long for this World]]'' (1948)\n* ''[[The Survivor and Others]]'' (1957) with [[H. P. Lovecraft]]\n* ''[[The Mask of Cthulhu]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[Lonesome Places]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[The Trail of Cthulhu]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[Mr. George and Other Odd Persons]]'' (1963) as Stephen Grendon\n* ''[[Colonel Markesan and Less Pleasant People]]'' (1966) with [[Mark Schorer]]\n* ''[[The Watchers Out of Time and Others]]'' (1974) with [[H. P. Lovecraft]]\n* ''[[Dwellers in Darkness]]'' (19