{"title_page": "Edith Maud Ellis", "text_new": "{{Short description|English Quaker and anti-war activist}}\n{{for2|English writer and women's rights activist|[[Edith Ellis]]|the American actress and playwright|[[Edith Ellis (playwright)]]|American women's rights activist|[[Edith Anna Ellis]]}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Edith Maud Ellis\n| image       =\n| image_size  =\n| alt         =\n| caption     =\n| father      = [[John Ellis (Liberal politician)|John Edward Ellis]]\n| mother      = [[Maria Rowntree]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1878|01|06|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Nottingham]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1963|03|27|1878|01|06|df=yes}}\n| death_place = \n| known_for   = Imprisoned anti-war activist\n}}\n\n'''Edith Maud Ellis''' was a [[Quakers|Quaker]] and was actively involved in supporting [[conscientious objector]]s during [[World War I]].\n\n==Early life==\n\nEdith Ellis and her identical twin sister [[Marian_Cripps,_Baroness_Parmoor|Marian]] were born on 6 January 1878, the daughters of [[John Ellis (Liberal politician)|John Edward Ellis]], MP and Maria (n\u00e9e Rowntree).\n\n==World War I==\n\nIn 1916, Edith became Treasurer of the Friends Service Committee, set up to support Quakers who became conscientious objectors.<ref name=\"mwsn\">\n{{cite web\n|title=Edith M Ellis\n|url=https://menwhosaidno.org/context/women/ellis_edith.html\n|website=The men who said No\n|publisher=Peace Pledge Union\n|accessdate=8 April 2020\n}}\n</ref>\nThis committee had been set up by [[Yearly Meeting]] in 1915, to advise men of enlistment age.<ref name=\"CandC\">\n{{cite book\n|first=John William\n|last=Graham\n|title=Conscription and conscience; a history, 1916-1919\n|date=1922\n|publisher=[[George Allen & Unwin]]\n|location=London\n|pages=161, 166, 167\n|accessdate=8 April 2020\n|url=https://archive.org/details/conscriptioncons00grahrich/\n|archivedate=2007-05-02\n|oclc=1042539796\n}}\n</ref>\n\nIn May 1918, the three officers of the Friends Service Committee were prosecuted under the [[Defence of the Realm Act 1914|Defence of the Realm Act]],\ncharged with publishing a pamphlet titled ''A Challenge to Militarism'' without submitting it to the Censor.\n\nIn their defence the Friends stated that:\n:''We feel that the declaration of Peace and goodwill is the duty of all Christians and ought not to be dependent upon the permission of any Government Official.''\n:''We therefore intend to continue the publication of such leaflets as we feel it our duty to put forth, without submitting them to the Censor ...''\nEdith Ellis was fined \u00a3100 plus 50 guineas costs or three months imprisonment.\nHarrison Barrow and Arthur Watts received six months imprisonment.<ref name=\"BQ\">\n{{cite book\n|last=Kennedy\n|first=Thomas C.\n|title=British Quakerism, 1860-1920: The Transformation\n|date=2001\n|publisher=Oxford University Press\n|isbn=0198270356\n|pages=347-360\n}}</ref>\n\nAn appeal was held in July 1918 but was dismissed. Edith refused to pay her fine and was imprisoned for three months in [[HM Prison Holloway|Holloway]].<ref name=\"CandC\"></ref>\n\n==Later life==\n\nIn 1919, Edith turned her family home, Wrea Head in [[Scalby,_North_Yorkshire|Scalby]], into a convalescent centre for released conscientious objectors.<ref name=\"Trust\"></ref>\n\nIn 1948, Edith gave Wrea Head and its contents to the North Riding County Council for the purposes of education.<ref name=\"Hall\">\n{{cite web\n|title=Heritage & Lifestyle\n|url=https://wreaheadhall.co.uk/heritage-lifestyle/\n|website=Wrea Head Hall\n|accessdate=8 April 2020\n}}\n</ref>\n\nEdith established the ''Edith Ellis Charitable Trust'' for general charitable purposes.<ref name=\"Trust\">\n{{cite web\n|title=History\n|url=https://theedithmellischaritabletrust.org/history/\n|website=The Edith M Ellis 1985 Charitable Trust\n|accessdate=8 April 2020\n}}\n</ref>\nThe Trust, now named ''The Edith M Ellis 1985 Charitable Trust'', \"... aims to give small grants to a broad range of Quaker and other UK registered charities or Non Governmental Organisations.\"<ref name=\"CC\">\n{{cite web\n|title=Charity overview\n|url=https://apps.charitycommission.gov.uk/Showcharity/RegisterOfCharities/CharityWithoutPartB.aspx?RegisteredCharityNumber=292835\n|website=Charity Commission\n|publisher=The Charity Commission for England and Wales\n|accessdate=10 April 2020\n}}\n</ref>\n\nEdith Ellis died on 27 March 1963.\n\n==References==\n\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n\n* [http://southlondonquakers.org.uk/nletr/emellis.php South London Quakers, Edith Maud Ellis (1878 \u2013 1963)]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ellis, Edith Maud}}\n[[Category:British anti\u2013World War I activists]]\n[[Category:1878 births]]\n[[Category:1963 deaths]]\n[[Category:English Quakers]]\n[[Category:Twin people from England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|English Quaker and anti-war activist}}\n{{for2|English writer and women's rights activist|[[Edith Ellis]]|the American actress and playwright|[[Edith Ellis (playwright)]]|American women's rights activist|[[Edith Anna Ellis]]}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Edith Maud Ellis\n| image       =\n| image_size  =\n| alt         =\n| caption     =\n| father      = [[John Ellis (Liberal politician)|John Edward Ellis]]\n| mother      = [[Maria Rowntree]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1878|01|06|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Nottingham]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1963|03|27|1878|01|06|df=yes}}\n| death_place = \n| known_for   = Imprisoned anti-war activist\n}}\n\n'''Edith Maud Ellis''' was a [[Quakers|Quaker]] and was actively involved in supporting [[conscientious objector]]s during [[World War I]].\n\n==Early life==\n\nEdith Ellis and her identical twin sister [[Marian_Cripps,_Baroness_Parmoor|Marian]] were born on 6 January 1878, the daughters of [[John Ellis (Liberal politician)|John Edward Ellis]], MP and Maria (n\u00e9e Rowntree).\n\n==World War I==\n\nIn 1916, Edith became Treasurer of the Friends Service Committee, set up to support Quakers who became conscientious objectors.<ref name=\"mwsn\">\n{{cite web\n|title=Edith M Ellis\n|url=https://menwhosaidno.org/context/women/ellis_edith.html\n|website=The men who said No\n|publisher=Peace Pledge Union\n|accessdate=8 April 2020\n}}\n</ref>\nThis committee had been set up by [[Yearly Meeting]] in 1915, to advise men of enlistment age.<ref name=\"CandC\">\n{{cite book\n|first=John William\n|last=Graham\n|title=Conscription and conscience; a history, 1916-1919\n|date=1922\n|publisher=[[George Allen & Unwin]]\n|location=London\n|pages=161, 166, 167\n|accessdate=8 April 2020\n|url=https://archive.org/details/conscriptioncons00grahrich/\n|archivedate=2007-05-02\n|oclc=1042539796\n}}\n</ref>\n\nIn May 1918, the three officers of the Friends Service Committee were prosecuted under the [[Defence of the Realm Act 1914|Defence of the Realm Act]],\ncharged with publishing a pamphlet titled ''A Challenge to Militarism'' without submitting it to the Censor.\n\nIn their defence the Friends stated that:\n:''We feel that the declaration of Peace and goodwill is the duty of all Christians and ought not to be dependent upon the permission of any Government Official.''\n:''We therefore intend to continue the publication of such leaflets as we feel it our duty to put forth, without submitting them to the Censor ...''\nEdith Ellis was fined \u00a3100 plus 50 guineas costs or three months imprisonment.\nHarrison Barrow and Arthur Watts received six months imprisonment.<ref name=\"BQ\">\n{{cite book\n|last=Kennedy\n|first=Thomas C.\n|title=British Quakerism, 1860-1920: The Transformation\n|date=2001\n|publisher=Oxford University Press\n|isbn=0198270356\n|pages=347-360\n}}</ref>\n\nAn appeal was held in July 1918 but was dismissed. Edith refused to pay her fine and was imprisoned for three months in [[HM Prison Holloway|Holloway]].<ref name=\"CandC\"></ref>\n\n==Later life==\n\nIn 1919, Edith turned her family home, Wrea Head in [[Scalby,_North_Yorkshire|Scalby]], into a convalescent centre for released conscientious objectors.<ref name=\"Trust\"></ref>\n\nIn 1948, Edith gave Wrea Head and its contents to the North Riding County Council for the purposes of education.<ref name=\"Hall\">\n{{cite web\n|title=Heritage & Lifestyle\n|url=https://wreaheadhall.co.uk/heritage-lifestyle/\n|website=Wrea Head Hall\n|accessdate=8 April 2020\n}}\n</ref>\n\nEdith established the ''Edith Ellis Charitable Trust'' for general charitable purposes.<ref name=\"Trust\">\n{{cite web\n|title=History\n|url=https://theedithmellischaritabletrust.org/history/\n|website=The Edith M Ellis 1985 Charitable Trust\n|accessdate=8 April 2020\n}}\n</ref>\nThe Trust, now named ''The Edith M Ellis 1985 Charitable Trust'', \"... aims to give small grants to a broad range of Quaker and other UK registered charities or Non Governmental Organisations.\"<ref name=\"CC\">\n{{cite web\n|title=Charity overview\n|url=https://apps.charitycommission.gov.uk/Showcharity/RegisterOfCharities/CharityWithoutPartB.aspx?RegisteredCharityNumber=292835\n|website=Charity Commission\n|publisher=The Charity Commission for England and Wales\n|accessdate=10 April 2020\n}}\n</ref>\n\nEdith Ellis died on 27 March 1963.\n\n==References==\n\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n\n* [http://southlondonquakers.org.uk/nletr/emellis.php South London Quakers, Edith Maud Ellis (1878 \u2013 1963)]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ellis, Edith Maud}}\n[[Category:British anti\u2013World War I activists]]\n[[Category:1878 births]]\n[[Category:1963 deaths]]\n[[Category:English Quakers]]\n[[Category:Rowntree family]]\n[[Category:Twin people from England]]\n", "name_user": "GhostInTheMachine", "label": "safe", "comment": "Not a York Rowntree", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edith_Maud_Ellis"}
{"title_page": "John Grigg (New Zealand politician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2014}}\n[[File:Ashburton - 7304141006.jpg|thumb|John Grigg Statue in Baring Square, [[Ashburton, New Zealand|Ashburton]]]]\n{{NZ parlbox header|nolist=true|align=left}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |start      = {{NZ election link year|1884}}\n |end        = 1885\n |term       = 9th\n |electorate = {{NZ electorate link|Wakanui}}\n |party      = Independent politician\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox footer}}\n'''John Grigg''' (21 April 1828 \u2013 5 November 1901) was a 19th-century [[Member of parliament|Member of Parliament]] in [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]], New Zealand.\n\nGrigg was born in [[Bodbrane]], [[Cornwall]], England on 21 April 1828<ref>{{cite book | ref = harv | editor-last = Scholefield | editor-first = Guy | editor-link = Guy Scholefield | title = A Dictionary of New Zealand Biography : A\u2013L | volume = I | year = 1940 | publisher = [[Department of Internal Affairs (New Zealand)|Department of Internal Affairs]] | location = Wellington | url = https://www.nzhistory.net.nz/files/documents/dnzb-1940/scholefield-dnzb-v1.pdf | accessdate = 16 July 2016 | page=332}}</ref> and baptised in the nearby [[Duloe, Cornwall|Duloe]] two days later.<ref name=\"DNZB Grigg\">{{DNZB|Lawrence |Morag |2g20|Grigg, John |16 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe briefly represented the [[Wakanui (New Zealand electorate)|Wakanui]] electorate from 23 July 1884 to 4 June 1885, when he resigned.<ref name=\"Wilson\">{{cite book |last= Wilson |first= James Oakley |title= New Zealand parliamentary record, 1840-1984 |edition= 4 |origyear= First ed. published 1913 |year= 1985 |publisher=V.R. Ward, Govt. Printer |location= Wellington |isbn= |oclc= 154283103 |page=201}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|New Zealand|Cornwall}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grigg, John}}\n[[Category:1828 births]]\n[[Category:1901 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the New Zealand House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:New Zealand MPs for South Island electorates]]\n[[Category:Cornish emigrants to New Zealand]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to New Zealand]]\n[[Category:19th-century New Zealand politicians]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2014}}\n[[File:Ashburton - 7304141006.jpg|thumb|John Grigg Statue in Baring Square, [[Ashburton, New Zealand|Ashburton]]]]\n{{NZ parlbox header|nolist=true|align=left}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |start      = {{NZ election link year|1884}}\n |end        = 1885\n |term       = 9th\n |electorate = {{NZ electorate link|Wakanui}}\n |party      = Independent politician\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox footer}}\n'''John Grigg''' (21 April 1828 \u2013 5 November 1901) was a 19th-century [[Member of parliament|Member of Parliament]] in [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]], New Zealand.\n\nGrigg was born in [[Bodbrane]], [[Cornwall]], England on 21 April 1828<ref>{{cite book | ref = harv | editor-last = Scholefield | editor-first = Guy | editor-link = Guy Scholefield | title = A Dictionary of New Zealand Biography : A\u2013L | volume = I | year = 1940 | publisher = [[Department of Internal Affairs (New Zealand)|Department of Internal Affairs]] | location = Wellington | url = https://www.nzhistory.net.nz/files/documents/dnzb-1940/scholefield-dnzb-v1.pdf | accessdate = 16 July 2016 | page=332}}</ref> and baptised in the nearby [[Duloe, Cornwall|Duloe]] two days later.<ref name=\"DNZB Grigg\">{{DNZB|Lawrence |Morag |2g20|Grigg, John |16 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe briefly represented the [[Wakanui (New Zealand electorate)|Wakanui]] electorate from 23 July 1884 to 4 June 1885, when he resigned.<ref name=\"Wilson\">{{cite book |last= Wilson |first= James Oakley |title= New Zealand parliamentary record, 1840-1984 |edition= 4 |origyear= First ed. published 1913 |year= 1985 |publisher=V.R. Ward, Govt. Printer |location= Wellington |isbn= |oclc= 154283103 |page=201}}</ref>\n